<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> M.L. King III, Sharpton say promoters in IBF scandal should be charged </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Boxing promoters who testified they paid
bribes for favors from the IBF should also face trial, according to
two civil rights leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King III and the Rev. Al Sharpton spoke Thursday
outside the federal courthouse where IBF founder Robert W. Lee has
been on trial on racketeering charges since mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   They have not attended the trial and did not take a position on
Lee's guilt or innocence, or whether Lee is being prosecuted
because he is black, as his defense lawyer suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know enough about the trial to comment about it,''
said Sharpton, president of the New York-based National Action
Network.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged they were concerned about statements made by two
major promoters, Bob Arum and Cedric Kushner, who testified last
month about their roles in $100,000 payoffs to the IBF.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other key witnesses, they testified without immunity.
Arum said he did not seek it; Kushner said prosecutors refused his
request.
</P>
<P>
   King, son of Martin Luther King Jr. and president of the
Atlanta-based Southern Christian Leadership Conference, said,
''There seems to be a double standard that must be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The ones who have admitted to crimes are not being
prosecuted,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   The lead prosecutor against Lee, Jose P. Sierra, said, ''We
can't comment on what charging decisions, if any, will be made.''
He expects to rest his case Friday.
</P>
<P>
   King and Sharpton also said their groups and the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People would have
hearings in the fall to explore whether black and Latino boxers are
losing opportunities because of bribery.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to criminal charges, Arum, who operates Top Rank of
Las Vegas; Kushner, of New York's Cedric Kushner Productions; and
other promoters in the IBF case could lose their licenses to put on
boxing matches.
</P>
<P>
   Their testimony is under scrutiny by officials in New Jersey and
Nevada - the most lucrative states for boxing because of their
casinos - as well as California, which has the most boxing matches
of any state, and New York.
</P>
<P>
   State boxing commissions are also looking at testimony regarding
the sport's biggest promoter, Don King, of Deerfield Beach, Fla.,
and the Duva family of Main Events Inc., of Totowa, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors identify Don King as an unindicted
coconspirator in the Lee case, supported by testimony that he was
the prime beneficiary of Lee's manipulations of the IBF rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton has long been friendly with Don King, but said that
would not matter: ''In our hearings, whether friend or foe, it
doesn't matter. We want to get to the bottom of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton's name surfaced during Kushner's testimony, when he
described a 1991 incident in which Don King and Lee were not
getting along.
</P>
<P>
   The IBF, at its annual convention in New Orleans, was
considering whether to give its approval to championship fights in
South Africa as its apartheid system began to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner, a native South African and naturalized U.S. citizen,
said he told Lee he favored the change.
</P>
<P>
   Kushner testified he believed that Don King arranged for
Sharpton to bring demonstrators against making the change.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said Thursday he went because he opposed apartheid, not
at the behest of Don King.
</P>
<P>
   Don King spokesman Greg Fritz has said he also opposed
apartheid, but could not say whether he had a role in the Sharpton
protest.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and other IBF officials are accused of taking $338,000 in a
span of more than a decade in exchange for favors and rigged
rankings. No promoters are on trial.
</P>
<P>
   As one of three major sanctioning bodies for boxing in the
world, the rankings and decisions of the East Orange-based IBF play
a large role in the purses earned by boxers, of which managers and
promoters get a cut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
