<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hoboken cop sues football players over beating  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Penn State quarterback Rashard Casey,
Syracuse safety Keeon Walker and a former teammate of theirs at
Hoboken High School are being sued by a police officer who says
they beat him unconscious outside a Hoboken bar in May.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Patrick D. Fitzsimmons does not know when he will return
to work and suffers from headaches, nausea and nightmares from the
beating, said his lawyer, Anthony J. Pope Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons, 34, of Hoboken, seeks an unspecified amount of
money as compensation for ''severe and painful injuries'' that have
brought ''significant loss in the quality and enjoyment of his
life,'' according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Casey and the third man, Desmond Miller, have pleaded innocent
to charges of aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Walker tried to stop the attack and was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   The three were sued based on interviews conducted with
witnesses, including an off-duty Jersey City officer, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons appeared with Pope at a news conference Thursday,
but Pope did not permit him to speak.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed June 29 in state Superior Court for Hudson
County in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   It accuses all three men of ''maliciously striking and kicking
plaintiff Fitzsimmons repeatedly about the head, face and body.''
</P>
<P>
   Police have said the attack may have been racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons, who is white, was at the Cadillac Bar in Hoboken,
where he met a friend, Elsa Ballantine, of East Orange, who is
black, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   They left about 2:30 a.m. on May 14, and were confronted on the
street by the defendants, who are black, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoboken Police Chief Carmen LaBruno has said Casey and Miller
spoke to the woman at the bar. He did not return a call seeking
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''What are you doing with him? You should be with us. You're one
of us,'' they said, according to the chief, which squared with
Pope's account.
</P>
<P>
   ''She responded to the extent, 'I don't want to be with you, I
want to be with him,''' Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody mentioned that Fitzsimmons was an officer, which
Fitzsimmons acknowledged before he was assaulted, Pope said. He was
not armed, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   According to LaBruno, Casey punched Fitzsimmons, and Casey and
Miller kicked the officer in the head once he had fallen, and
continued to kick him after he lost consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Walker told Casey and Miller to stop because Fitzsimmons was a
police officer, LaBruno has said.
</P>
<P>
   Casey, 22, a senior this fall, remains on the team pending the
outcome of an investigation by a Penn State judicial review
committee, school spokesman William M. Mahon said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State football coach Joe Paterno has said he expects Casey
''will be exonerated when all of the facts are examined.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey's lawyer, Dennis D. McAlevy, said, ''Mr. Casey, as far as
I know, was just walking down the street, and got arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My investigation has disclosed that off-duty Police Officer
Fitzsimmons was visibly intoxicated and embracing and kissing and
rubbing his body against a woman other than his wife in the middle
of Newark Street just prior to the alleged assault,'' McAlevy said
Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ''What relevance does that have?'' Pope responded. ''What
matters is without any provocation my client was attacked.''
Fitzsimmons is married, but was not out with his wife that night.
They have no children, Pope said.
</P>
<P>
   No listing could be found for Ballantine.
</P>
<P>
   Casey, who led Penn State to a victory in the Alamo Bowl last
year, graduated from Hoboken in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, 20, of Hoboken, a redshirt sophomore this fall, told his
coach, Paul Pasqualoni, that he tried to break up the fight, said
Sue Edson, a Syracuse sports spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Walker remains on the team and was moved in spring practice from
running back to strong safety, Edson said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 22, of Jersey City, could not be reached for comment. No
listing could be found.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons is a five-year veteran who teaches tolerance
training in the community policing division.
</P>
</TEXT>
