<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Kids Die in Nicaragua Earthquake  </HEADLINE>
By FILADELFO ALEMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALLE LA LAGUNA, Nicaragua (AP) -- An earthquake shook Nicaragua
on Thursday, killing two children, injuring dozens and damaging
homes in several poor villages east of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon quake, with a preliminary magnitude of 5.9, was
centered in Laguna de Apoyo, about 30 miles east of the capital
Managua, the Nicaraguan Institute of Territorial Studies said.
</P>
<P>
   An 11-year-old girl and a 4-year-old boy died when a house wall
fell on them, Nicaraguan Vice President Enrique Bolanos said.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake was felt across the country, but deaths and
injuries apparently were limited to Valle La Laguna, a small hamlet
25 miles east of the capital of Managua.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never before had I felt an earthquake like this,'' said
90-year-old Elvira Gallegos.
</P>
<P>
   Army helicopters evacuated five of the 31 injured, while
firefighters and the Red Cross rescued 26 others after clearing
rock and trees away from a blocked highway leading into the town.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of houses, mostly unstable cement and adobe structures,
were damaged and some were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In San Juan de Oriente, a town of about 5,000, residents ran
into the streets, clutching their belongings and bracing for
aftershocks, which came shortly after the first tremors.
</P>
<P>
   The town's church and some houses suffered minor damage. Roof
tiles were shaken off and statues fell in the cemetery.
</P>
</TEXT>
