<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protestant March Nixed in N. Ireland  </HEADLINE>
By SHAWN POGATCHNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Protestant militants rallied
across Northern Ireland for a fifth straight night in frustration
at being denied the right to parade through the main Catholic
section of Portadown.
</P>
<P>
   Following heavy criticism from many quarters over the week's
violent clashes in the British province, road blocades and other
protests remained largely peaceful Friday -- a shift attributed in
part to the imminent funeral of a revered Protestant sports star.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50,000 mourners were expected to attend services
Friday afternoon for Joey Dunlop, the Ulster-born motorcycling
daredevil who won five world racing championships before suffering
a fatal crash last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   His death and legacy have competed for local headlines all week
alongside the riots. His grieving family and Orange Order leaders
appealed Thursday for a halt to the violence before his funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ''I make this genuine plea to everyone: Let's remember the great
ambassador for Northern Ireland, Joey Dunlop. Let's have a quiet
day,'' said Robert Saulters, grand master of the Orange Order,
Northern Ireland's major Protestant fraternal group, whose
summertime marches always raise sectarian passions.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of this week's violence-prone Orange protests --
triggered when British authorities told Orangemen they could not
parade this Sunday past hostile Catholics on Portadown's Garvaghy
Road -- hoped Saulters' appeal represented a newfound determination
to deter troublemakers. They responded to the Orange Order's call
last weekend for mass protests by attacking police and soldiers
with bricks, firecrackers and gasoline bombs.
</P>
<P>
   But many fear that Friday could be the lull before another storm
of street confrontations. Saulters and other Orange leaders remain
set on defying Sunday's parade restrictions in Portadown, where
police and soldiers since 1998 have blocked their annual march from
reaching Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just getting rested up for the weekend,'' quipped Johnny
McCullough, a Protestant teen-ager who said he'd taken part in
Belfast riots for three nights straight.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday he was sipping alcoholic cider with friends on a
tattered old sofa left on a sidewalk by rioters. Two units of
police sat nearby eating sandwiches in the backs of their armored
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier that night in a nearby house, police had seized crates
of bottles and a tin of gasoline -- the building blocks for
potentially lethal Molotov cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   ''But there's plenty more bottles than peelers (police) in
Belfast,'' McCullough said, predicting, ''The weekend's going to be
wild.''
</P>
<P>
   And the climax of Orange marching plans won't come until
Wednesday, the so-called Twelfth holiday. Tens of thousands of
Protestants are expected to parade throughout Northern Ireland to
commemorate the 1690 defeat of Catholic King James II at the hands
of Protestant William of Orange.
</P>
<P>
   British authorities on Thursday ordered one Belfast parade
rerouted away from a hostile Catholic district, but two other
disputed Twelfth parades opposed by Catholics were given approval.
That compromise set the stage for possible protests by hard-liners
from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Thursday they had arrested 43 Protestant rioters
during 109 attacks on police and army units this week. Thirty-two
police officers and one soldier were wounded. At least 37 houses,
mostly Catholic-owned, had been attacked, while 34 vehicles were
hijacked and burned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
