<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angels 5, Mariners 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Mo Vaughn and Tim Salmon homered and
Jarrod Washburn pitched five shutout innings to lead the Anaheim
Angels to a 5-1 victory over the Seattle Mariners on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn (5-2) held the team with the fewest hits in the AL to
three singles and a double to ruin the Mariners' bid to win 10
consecutive series.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander, who took a no-hitter into the seventh against
Oakland in his previous start, struck out five and walked three and
allowed fewer than three runs for the fifth time in six outings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners, who haven't been shutout since opening day against
Boston, did not get a runner to third base until the eighth when
one-out singles by Edgar Martinez off Mike Fyhrie and John Olerud
off Mike Holtz put runners at the corners. Jay Buhner lined Mark
Petkovsek's first pitch to left field to drive in Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   After preventing the Mariners from scoring in the first inning
for the first time in their four-game split, the Angels took the
lead against Paul Abbott (5-3) in the bottom of the first on
Vaughn's two-out solo homer to center field. It was his 22nd of the
season and his team-high 64th RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad drew a leadoff walk in the third and scored on
Salmon's two-out homer to center for a 3-0 lead. Salmon's 18 homers
are one more than he hit in 98 games last season, when he missed 2&AMP;frac12;
months because of a sprained left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Spiezio, starting at third base because of first-time
All-Star Troy Glaus' 1-for-29 drought, increased the lead to 5-0 in
the sixth with a bases-loaded two-run single that chased Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander was charged with five runs, five hits and five
walks in 5 1-3 innings, after going 4-0 with a 2.13 ERA in his
previous six starts.
</P>
<P>
   The loss reduced Seattle's lead in the AL West to three games
over Oakland. It also marked the first time the Mariners failed to
win a series since May 29-31, when they lost two of three to
Chicago at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Rickey Henderson drew his 2,019th career walk in the fifth
inning to tie Ted Williams for the second-most walks in major
league history. Babe Ruth tops the list with 2,062. ... Angels LHP
Kent Mercker, hospitalized for 12 days after a cerebral hemorrhage
forced him out of his May 11 start, passed a stress test on
Wednesday after last week's angiogram came back negative. ''I'm
planning on pitching in July,'' said Mercker, who returned to the
Angels' clubhouse last Friday for the first time. ''In my mind, I'm
done being monitored. I've been going crazy sitting around and not
being able to do anything.'' ... Glaus batted for Orlando Palmeiro
in the seventh and walked. ... Mariners CF Mike Cameron was a late
scratch because of stiffness in his right knee. ... Angels RHP Tim
Belcher was placed on the 15-day DL because of a strained right
flexor muscle in his elbow -- the same injury that forced him to
undergo surgery last December.
</P>
</TEXT>
