<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Talks Won't Divide Democrats  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE FARROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Reaching an agreement on trade language won't
be easy, but Democrats working on party policy for the next four
years insist it's possible.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Sen. Dick Durbin said at a hearing Thursday to draft
the party's platform that the issue continues to divide Democrats.
But he also said he was certain that the committee would be able to
reach some consensus when it meets Friday to draft the document on
issues, goals and policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't gloss over it, there will be some differences,'' said
Durbin, who co-chairs the platform committee.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Blinder, an adviser to Vice President Al Gore and a former
Federal Reserve vice chairman, urged the drafting committee to
embrace open trade.
</P>
<P>
   ''America gets cheaper, better and more preferred goods and that
raises the standard of living,'' said Blinder, now a professor of
economics at Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
   He was among some 50 witnesses who addressed the committee
Thursday at the University of Missouri-St. Louis. Members will use
those comments when they draft the platform that will be discussed
later this month in Cleveland. The document will then go before the
national convention in Los Angeles, which begins Aug. 14, for
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's simply not true -- and history speaks clearly to this --
that open trade causes unemployment,'' Blinder said. ''Imports have
soared in America over the last four years, growing at an
annualized real growth rate in excess of 12 percent. Yet during
this exact period unemployment has fallen and we have created 15
million new jobs in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Durbin said Democrats would work with unions to
ensure any policy on trade includes safeguards to protect American
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina Gov. Jim Hunt, who chairs the drafting committee,
suggested there would be no platform surprises for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''My sense is that much of this is what he has already had to
say and what he has already proposed,'' Hunt said. ''I think this
is a platform he can run on and he can win on.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, committee members heard from Mary Leigh Blek,
president of the Million Mom March, who urged them to stand strong
on gun control. There was no discussion of the death penalty, which
has become an issue nationwide and which Gore supports. Durbin said
the committee had discussed the death penalty on its own before the
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Blek, a Republican, told the committee she has been disappointed
by the GOP's efforts to block gun control measures in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   She wants gun owners to take safety classes and be held
accountable if their guns are used for harm.
</P>
<P>
   Durbin said he was pleased by Blek's appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm thrilled to have a lady come forward who started the
Million Mom March, and tell us she's a registered Republican but
when it comes to gun safety she knows this is the party that takes
it seriously,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Maury, president of the Business Roundtable, an association
of corporate chief executives, advised the committee on what to do
with one result of the economic prosperity -- the sizable federal
budget surplus. He suggested using some of it to give business
owners a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion, however, raised the ire of Hunt and committee
member Christopher Edley Jr., a professor at Harvard Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm disappointed you focused on using the surplus to cut
taxes,'' Edley told Maury. ''I'd urge the Business Round-table not
to be attached to tax cuts, but to make investments in education.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the witnesses present Thursday, the platform
drafting committee received comments from 1,600 people who
submitted them to the Web site SpeakOut.com.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said it was the first time a major political party had
allowed citizens to electronically submit their ideas and
suggestions for a platform.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.SpeakOut.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.dncplatform.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
