<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Propose Mining Rules  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ZUCKERBROD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government would assume more
responsibility at underground coal mines under proposed new rules
aimed at reducing black-lung disease.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for overhauling the system for sampling,
detecting and controlling dust in mines. It was made public
Thursday and comes after the United Mine Workers of America filed a
lawsuit seeking changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Underground coal miners must have confidence that the system
being used to test the air they breath is producing accurate
results,'' Labor Secretary Alexis M. Herman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, mine operators are responsible for sampling dust
levels. They submit the samples to the Labor Department's Mine
Safety Health Administration, which determines whether miners are
overexposed to the kind of dust that can cause black lung and other
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   For years, miners and their advocates have charged that
companies failed to accurately measure dust or doctored their
samples to meet government standards.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new proposal, the federal government will be
responsible for taking samples. About 100 federal inspectors are
expected to be hired to help with that task.
</P>
<P>
   ''This gets away from the fox guarding the hen house problem,''
said Davitt McAteer, assistant secretary of labor for mine safety
and health.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 86,000 U.S. coal miners working primarily in
Wyoming, West Virginia and Kentucky. The government estimates about
1,400 current or former miners die each year of black-lung disease.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Watzman, vice president of safety and health for the
National Mining Association, said the companies are ready to rid
themselves of sampling duties.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really a no-win proposition for the operators today,''
Watzman said, noting that companies are suspected of cheating
whenever the findings meet government regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed changes, to be published Friday in the Federal
Register, adopt recommendations by an advisory committee that
included mining industry and labor representatives. Under the plan:
</P>
<P>
   --The Mine Safety Health Administration would verify the
effectiveness of mine operators' dust-control measures. No
verification now is required.
</P>
<P>
   --Dust samples, collected six times per year, will be taken
during entire shifts. Now, the samples generally are collected over
eight-hour periods, although miners often work 10 and 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   --Inspectors will analyze dust levels in each area where miners
work. Currently, sample results from different parts of a mine are
averaged and do not take into account working in a specific area
breathing extremely dusty air.
</P>
<P>
   --Miners' representatives may observe the sampling.
</P>
<P>
   The United Mine Workers reacted cautiously to the proposed
changes. Joe Main, health and safety administrator for the union,
said he wanted to review them before commenting.
</P>
<P>
   Main said the lawsuit, which is still pending, prompted the
latest government action.
</P>
<P>
   But McAteer denied that, saying the proposal has been in the
works for five years.
</P>
<P>
   A public comment period on the proposal is expected to last
until Aug. 24, after which the rules will be finalized.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Federal Register:
http://www.access.gpo.gov/su--docs/aces/aces140.html
</P>
<P>
   Mine Safety Health Administration: http://www.msha.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 0127 </TRAILER>
