<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Settlement Loan Unsettled  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY DUNPHY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- World Bank directors try again Friday to
decide whether to approve a $40 million loan that would move poor
Chinese farmers to traditionally Tibetan lands after failing to
reach agreement in 6&AMP;frac12; hours of talks.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's board of directors spent much of Thursday reviewing
the project, which is opposed by the United States and pro-Tibetan
forces. But they were unable to reach a decision and will resume
talks Friday, bank officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bank managers have proposed another 15 to 18 months of social
and environmental studies in an effort to get a green light for the
project from the 24-member board, said the officials, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, the bank's major shareholder, along with
other governments that oppose the loan, want these studies to be
made public. And Bank President James Wolfensohn had recommended a
delay while the studies are carried out.
</P>
<P>
   But China and other borrowing governments are resisting, said
one person familiar with the talks.
</P>
<P>
   China is reluctant to see teams of international consultants
making repeated visits to the remote area in western Qinghai
province where the farmers would be resettled. China has a seat on
the 24-member bank board that will make the final decision on the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Under bank procedure, such project studies usually are released
after a loan is approved. The United States also wants another vote
on the project taken after the studies are completed.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-Tibetan opponents of the loan said the fact the directors
were unable to agree is a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a reflection of the divisiveness of the project,''
said John Acklerly of the International Campaign for Tibet. ''Such
disagreements are rare at the World Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the loan would be used to resettle 58,000
impoverished Chinese and Hui Muslim farmers in lands that are the
traditional homeland for 4,000 Tibetan and Mongol herders.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-Tibetan groups contend resettlement would aid China's effort
to dilute its minority Tibetan population. Tibet's exiled spiritual
leader, the Dalai Lama, said last month after a meeting with
President Clinton that the bank initiative ''would be a source of
more problems'' and should not proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Several protesters from the Campaign for Tibet camped out in
front of bank headquarters for the fourth day Thursday, calling for
cancellation of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups object to the part of the plan that would
underwrite construction of dams and irrigation canals in the
resettlement area.
</P>
<P>
   China insisted last week the project is supported by those who
would be relocated and by the Tibetans living in the province. The
Beijing government said the initiative would also raise living
standards and would strictly adhered to Chinese and World Bank
requirements.
</P>
</TEXT>
