<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's Fox Promises More Openess  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- More interaction, less presidentialism and
greater honesty. That's what Vicente Fox says he'll use to change
the aloof style of the Mexican presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Never one to shun a microphone, President-elect Fox said in a
televised interview Thursday that ''we are going to have a couple
of conferences a week,'' as well as ''interviews everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing President Ernesto Zedillo held only a few news
conferences during his six-year term. He promised regular briefings
when he first took office, then quickly dropped the idea.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three days after his victory, Fox seems to have
been everywhere, giving dozens of interviews. At times, both
national television networks were broadcasting separate interviews
with him at the same time -- one live, one taped.
</P>
<P>
   Fox even has appeared on the top two prime-time comedy shows of
the national Televisa network. He called to jokingly threaten
comedian Adal Ramones on Tuesday after a satirical piece on Fox. A
day later, Fox was on television ''interviewing'' Armando Hoyos -- a
comic intellectual played by Eugenio Derbez.
</P>
<P>
   Fox ''is his own chief of public relations,'' adviser Jorge
Castaneda told the Radio Red network Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   While Zedillo tends to appear in stiff and scripted television
addresses, Fox is far more relaxed, often gesticulating with his
hands and absent-mindedly massaging his cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, however, had been a relatively reserved economist --
never a politician -- before running for the presidency and seemed
uncomfortable when faced with tough or silly questions.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, naturally garrulous, has been running campaigns almost
constantly since 1990 as an opposition candidate. More often than
not, he has dealt with pro-government news media opposed to him.
</P>
<P>
   That may have fed his desire to grab whatever space he could get
in the press or on the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   When he was elected governor of Guanajuato state in 1995, Fox
spoke to reporters -- local, national and foreign -- for hours in a
hotel in the state capital of Leon.
</P>
<P>
   Some reporters left to report other stories and returned several
hours later to find Fox still sitting and talking. Even then, he
made little secret he was seeking the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's constant appearances on television and on the radio also
have a clear purpose: to ease the fears and confusion of Mexicans
who have never before experienced a leader who was not from the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   He also has promised to tour the country to listen to local
concerns and assure former foes that he will not take revenge.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate who referred to PRI as a haven of ''scorpions,''
''black snakes'' and ''toads'' has dramatically softened his tone.
</P>
<P>
   He promised Thursday that federal workers -- most of them PRI
members -- will be retained so long as they accept changes in
culture that include greater honesty and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anybody who adapts to that will be there for six years,'' the
length of the presidential term, he said in the Televisa interview.
</P>
<P>
   He also repeated his vow to keep a distance from his National
Action Party, or PAN. The outgoing party historically existed to
serve the presidents it put in power.
</P>
<P>
   He also vowed to be a less-dominant leader in a country
accustomed to presidents who were near-dictators.
</P>
<P>
   ''Presidentialism ended with me. It has radically ended,'' Fox
said in a long interview published Thursday by the left-leaning
newspaper La Jornada -- which generally had been hostile to his
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am going to be a president who serves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 0141 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000707.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak To Offer Concessions At Summit  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak will arrive
at the U.S.-sponsored Mideast summit next week prepared to offer
the Palestinians an expanded presence in a reshaped Jerusalem along
with admission of thousands of refugees whose families already live
in Israel, according to two well-placed Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
   Stressing the concessions must be matched by conciliatory
Palestinian moves, the officials said Thursday the future of
Jerusalem was the toughest issue on the table and may be excluded
from a settlement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Less progress has been made on Jerusalem than any other issue in
the negotiations leading up to the summit President Clinton will
stage beginning Tuesday at Camp David, Md. By contrast, the two
sides have made considerable headway on the question of how much
land Israel will turn over to Yasser Arafat for a state, said the
officials, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, for instance, may not insist on retaining the strategic
Jordan Valley, provided Israel can maintain a security presence
there at least for some time, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual disclosure of Barak's likely stance on core issues
at the summit appeared to be part of an effort to project him as a
reasonable Israeli leader and to coax matching concessions from
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, at least, the Palestinian leader is demanding transfer
of virtually all of the West Bank, Gaza and east Jerusalem -- more
land than Barak is prepared to relinquish. And Barak intends to
keep Jerusalem united and Israel's capital, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak is prepared to consider expanding areas of the city
already under day-to-day Arab control in exchange for incorporating
nearby Jewish settlements into the predominantly Jewish area of the
city, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   On refugees, Barak is willing to consider permitting tens of
thousands of Palestinians to settle in Israel if they have family
members there, but he will not accept the idea they have a legal
right to return, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The precedent is Israel's acceptance of 60,000 to 70,000
Palestinian Arabs in a program of reuniting families that was in
force between Israel's founding in 1948 and the Mideast war of
1967, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of today's refugees would be absorbed in the
Palestinian state, while others would receive assistance under a
worldwide funding campaign.
</P>
<P>
   East Jerusalem was occupied by Jordan before it was captured by
Israeli troops in the 1967 Mideast war and reunited with the
predominantly Jewish Western part of the ancient city.
</P>
<P>
   In Arab neighborhoods, Palestinians already run their day-to-day
affairs. This area can be expanded beyond Jerusalem's current
boundaries to incorporate predominantly Arab areas, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   But they stressed that was contingent on Israel absorbing into
the city some of the nearby suburbs now on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything about Jerusalem is on the table, everything is
discussable,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about Barak's possible concessions led two Israeli
political parties to announce this week they were quitting his
government.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright continued her
campaign to rally Arab and Jewish support for the summit,
</P>
<P>
   She met with Foreign Minister Habib ben Yahia of Tunisia and
spoke on the telephone with King Mohammed of Morocco, the State
Department spokesman Richard Boucher said. Also, Albright met with
a coalition of American Arab groups and, separately, with members
of the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish
Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he hopes the summit could conclude in a few
days. Palestinian officials said Thursday a two-stage summit was
under consideration, with the second round in August.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli officials said that approach had been discussed with
the Palestinians and the U.S. hosts. But a U.S. official, speaking
on condition of anonymity, denied that and said Washington wants to
reach an accord in one stage.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are due in Washington this
weekend for pre-summit talks on Sunday and Monday, and Albright
plans to meet with them, Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Boucher assured Tokyo that Albright was skipping
a high-level conference next week in Japan only because of the
urgency of Mideast talks.
</P>
<P>
   Albright explained to Foreign Minister Yohei Kono in a half-hour
telephone call why she would not attend the foreign ministers
meeting and he ''expressed his understanding of the critical timing
of the Middle East peace talks,'' Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers of Britain, Canada, France, Germany,
Italy, Japan and Russia are due to meet at Miyazaki on July 12-13
to prepare for a Group of Eight summit meeting on Okinawa July
21-23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 0142 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
