<DOCNO> APW20000707.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advice Offered For Bull Running  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL WOOLLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAMPLONA, Spain (AP) -- Safety tip No. 1 for running with
1,500-pound bulls bred to be quick, ornery and relentless: don't
yell at them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, don't do anything that has even the slightest chance of
distracting the hulking beasts which are the star attraction of
Spain's most internationally known summer event, the San Fermin
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans of the half-mile course, which winds through narrow
streets in Pamplona's old quarter, say that despite all the
drinking and merriment that goes on almost nonstop for eight days,
they take their running very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   After all, 13 people have died at San Fermin since
record-keeping started in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   ''This not a game,'' said Cesar Garro, a 29-year-old auto
factory worker who has run in the last six festivals. ''The streets
belong to the bull.''
</P>
<P>
   They rule the streets for two or three minutes, if all goes
well, starting at 8 a.m. sharp each morning for a week, as six
fighting bulls are freed from a corral and rumble down a fenced
route to a bullring where they will face matadors and certain death
by afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the runners sport the traditional festival garb of white
shirt, white pants, red bandanna and red sash around the waist.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all carry rolled up newspapers. One idea is that if a
friend falls and a bull attacks, you throw the paper to the ground
so it will unfurl and distract the bull. In fact, some foolhardy
runners use the paper to tap bulls on the rump.
</P>
<P>
   During the run, the animals are accompanied by steers which are
supposed to serve as guides, keeping the bulls more or less in a
cluster.
</P>
<P>
   But many things can and do go wrong. Hoofs provide poor traction
on cobblestone, so sometimes the bulls slip and fall, particularly
at one rather sharp turn about midway through the run.
</P>
<P>
   A fallen bull is even more dangerous. Separated from the herd,
he gets up confused and may run in the wrong direction. Seeing
nothing but people instead of fellow bulls, the toro can get
nervous and charge.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting bulls are amazingly agile for their size. In bullfights
they sometimes leap over a 5-foot-tall wooden fence that surrounds
the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Making things worse, human thrill-seekers also fall at San
Fermin. The festival has become so popular and the runs so crowded
that, veterans say, half the trick is to be aware of who or what is
nearby as you sprint, trying to see in all directions at once.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of many novices among the estimated 2,000 people
who take part in each run poses another risk. ''I've seen people
running with backpacks, or running while shooting video cameras,''
said Garro.
</P>
<P>
   He and other veterans insist that another important rule of San
Fermin is that if you fall, don't get up. Curl up, cover your head
with your arms and just hope you don't get trampled or gored, they
say.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you get up, there's a 90 percent chance something will go
wrong,'' said Inigo Etxeberria, 28.
</P>
<P>
   He said the last person gored to death at San Fermin, Matthew
Tassio, 22, of Glen Ellyn, Ill., made the mistake of getting up
after he went down in front of the Pamplona town hall in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bull never even changed direction. It just barreled right
into him,'' Etxeeberria said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they remain on their feet, runners can keep up with the
bulls for only five or six seconds because the animals are so fast.
Veterans compare the experience to merging into fast-moving traffic
on a highway, then trying to get off quickly.
</P>
<P>
   If you do it right, for a few Adrenalin-fueled seconds you're
close enough to the bull to smell it, to hear its raspy pant. ''It
sounds like a locomotive engine,'' Etxeberria said.
</P>
<P>
   Runners choose different stretches of the route for their brief
run. All are considered dangerous, although for different reasons.
Many daredevil veterans prefer the opening 200 yards or so, a steep
hill leading up and away from the corral.
</P>
<P>
   It's risky because the street is particularly narrow, the bulls
are fresh and they are running their fastest -- bulls move better
uphill than downhill because their front legs are shorter than
their hind legs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 0158 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000707.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kodak: Air emissions down at Rochester facility  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Eastman Kodak Co.'s annual report to the
U-S Environmental Protection Agency claimed the photographic giant
has continued to reduce the amount of chemicals released into the
air.
</P>
<P>
   According to figures released by the company, there has been a
16 percent decline in chemical emissions last year at Kodak Park in
Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 percent drop in toxic emissions in 1999 marks the 11th
straight annual drop in the figure, which companies nationwide must
file with government regulators by July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Kodak's releases into the Rochester area's air, water and land
totaled 5.2 million pounds last year. The total has fallen 75
percent since 1987, the first year for which reports were required.
</P>
<P>
   The company has spent hundreds of millions of dollars on
environmental protection and cleanup here since the late 1980s, and
has paid several million dollars in fines to federal and state
regulators for various infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the marked reductions in its toxic releases, Kodak Park
in Rochester has been ranked the state's largest polluter and is a
frequent target of environmental critics.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported Thursday that air releases of the chemical
that critics focus on most often - methylene chloride, a solvent
used in film-base manufacture - dropped 17.6 percent last year
compared with the year before. Releases of the possible human
carcinogen totaled 1.4 million pounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
