<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 02:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Considers China Visit  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM FOREMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- If the government allows Mayor Frank Hseih
to go to China next week, the head of Taiwan's second-largest city
will become one of the most prominent politicians to visit the
mainland since the two territories split amid civil war 51 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hseih, mayor of Kaosiung, Taiwan's biggest port, said Friday
that the laws restricting top leaders from freely traveling to
China should not apply to him. The government was expected to
decide later in the day whether Hsieh could go.
</P>
<P>
   Although hundreds of Taiwanese tourists and investors visit
China daily, the island's laws do not allow officials in sensitive
positions -- including ministers and vice ministers in the Cabinet --
to freely travel to China.
</P>
<P>
   However, the law is not clear about whether the mayors of
Taiwan's two largest cities, Taipei and Kaohsiung, need government
permission to go to China.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Hsieh, a former attorney, argued that the law could
not prevent him from traveling to China and that his trip would
merely be a city-to-city exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ''Talking directly is better than talking indirectly,'' he told
reporters in Kaohsiung. ''Understanding is better than
misunderstanding. Goodwill is better than war.''
</P>
<P>
   Hsieh's proposed trip would come at a sensitive time.
China-Taiwan relations have been especially tense since Taiwanese
President Chen Shui-bian's March election upset ended more than
five decades of Nationalist Party rule on Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the significance of the mayor's proposed visit, Hsieh
was recently elected chairman of the Democratic Progressive Party,
whose members include the president.
</P>
<P>
   Hsieh announced this week that Xiamen Mayor Zhu Yayan had sent
him an informal letter inviting him to visit. Hsieh said he
immediately accepted the invitation and wanted to travel to China
on July 10-13 before he takes over as the DPP's chairman on July
22.
</P>
<P>
   Kaohsiung is across the Taiwan Strait from Xiamen, which is a
key outlet for exported goods made by Taiwanese-owned mainland
factories.
</P>
<P>
   Premier Tang Fei and the Mainland Affairs Council, which handles
Taiwan's China policy, on Friday were determining whether Hsieh's
proposed trip to the southern city of Xiamen would be legal, said
Lin Chong-pin, the council's vice chairman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 0242 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000707.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Stock Market Opens July 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Vietnam will launch its long-awaited stock
market in Ho Chi Minh City on July 20 but so far only two companies
are listed, State Securities Commission Chairman Nguyen Duc Quang
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The government has been planning a stock exchange for several
years, but had postponed the launch because of a lack of companies
willing to list and concerns the market will expose Vietnam's
financial system to unnecessary risk.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Ho Chi Minh City-based Refrigeration Electrical
Engineering and the Cables and Telecommunications Materials
joint-stock company in neighboring Dong Nai province have been
licensed to list their shares.
</P>
<P>
   But the government says the main source of commodities for the
exchange floor will be government bonds, bank bonds and project
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Quang told Dow Jones Newswires Friday he hopes several more
companies will be approved before the market's launch.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 400 of some 5,900 state-owned enterprises have been
privatized under a government program launched seven years ago in
hopes of mobilizing public savings, believed to total billions of
dollars. That has become increasingly important with a slowdown in
foreign investment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 0247 </TRAILER>
