<HEADLINE> Dow Jumps 111; Nasdaq Climbs 64  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose in morning trading on Wall Street
Friday as investors welcomed the latest indication that the Federal
Reserve has been succeeding in its campaign to gently slow down the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   In late morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 111.37 at 10,592.84.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was up 16.74 at 1,473.41, and the Nasdaq composite index
rose 64.95 to 4,025.52.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department reported early Friday that total employment
rose by only 11,000 in June, the smallest increase in four years.
It was the latest sign that the economy has been cooling in
response to a series of interest rate increases from the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been hoping that the Fed may be nearly done with
its current campaign to fight back inflationary pressures and may
be ready to leave rates alone for the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   An improving outlook for interest rates put a glow on financial
companies, which benefit most from steady or declining interest
rates. Chase Manhattan rose $2 to $50, Bank One rose $1.063 to
$29.875 and BankAmerica rose $1.563 to $47.563.
</P>
<P>
   The positive jobs report helped calm the market, which has been
acting jittery over the past week ahead of second-quarter earnings
announcements. Tech stocks took a beating on Wednesday after
Computer Associates warned that its profits would not meet
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Gainers on the stock market Friday included Texas Instruments,
up $2.875 at $70; Home Depot, up $3 at $54.25 and Gateway, up $5 at
$61.75.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm bucked the upward trend, slipping $5.563 to $56.125 on
a report that Korean wireless operators would not use technology
from the telecom company. Yahoo also slipped $5.687 to $116.688 as
a brokerage house downgraded the stock, citing concerns about
revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining ones by a 7-to-4 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 292.03 million
shares, up slightly from the same time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 2.89 to 526.21.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
