<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavs Boiling Mad at Heat Wave  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT H. REID
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- With temperatures in Kosovo and the
Balkans reaching record levels, shopkeeper Emin Bajraktari is
boiling mad.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is it hot -- there's no electricity and water supplies
are chancy at best.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because of the lack of electricity, I can't operate my
refrigerator,'' the 38-year-old grocer fumed. ''I've had to throw
away meat because it spoiled. I'm losing hundreds of dollars every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The record-setting Balkan heat wave has sent temperatures
soaring above 104 degrees in Kosovo, compounding already critical
problems of electricity and water supplies more than a year after
NATO and the United Nations took over the province from the Serbs
following a 78-day bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble started Tuesday when a 400-kilowatt line tripped,
forcing a shutdown of the 17-year-old, coal-fired power plant at
Obilic, just outside the capital Pristina. Workers couldn't restart
the faulty generator because one motor and the auxiliary
transformer failed.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Lindmeier, the spokesman for the European Union, which
oversees the plant, could not say Friday when repairs could be
made. In the worst case, he added, repairs could take months if the
transformer has to be sent to its manufacturer in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the prospect of a lengthy shutdown, workers tried to
start another generator at Obilic. That didn't work, because the
water container used to produce steam was leaking so badly. Crews
fired up yet another, but a pump failed and the whole system
collapsed at 3:25 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, the U.N. administration could import emergency power
from neighboring countries on the same Balkan regional grid. But
the heat wave has stretched supplies in Albania, Romania and
Bulgaria to the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Lindmeier said some additional power might be available from
Bulgaria next week. In order to power hospitals and other
high-priority locations, Kosovo is importing some electricity from
-- of all places -- Serbia. But its not enough to power homes and
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the general collapse of infrastructure means there's
little people can do to beat the heat. Outdoor cafes cannot serve
coffee because the machines need power. The city's swimming pool
has closed to conserve water.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Ghedini, the spokeswoman for the U.N. refugee agency, said
people are being urged to drink more water. That's not so simple,
however, since the electricity shortage means pumps cannot get
water to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Most people in Pristina cannot count on running water for more
than a couple of hours each day.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions are even worse for the thousands of people who don't
even have a proper roof over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   On a hill in the village of Vukovc, about 20 miles west of the
capital, Hida Bogicici and 10 members of her family live in a tent
on the grounds of their home, which was destroyed in last year's
Serb crackdown on ethnic Albanian militants.
</P>
<P>
   ''During the winter, we couldn't stay inside because rainwater
was always leaking into the tent,'' she said. ''Now, it's too hot
and with 11 people in one tent, it's too cramped. Mostly we stay
outside in the shade.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the European Union awarded a $40 million contract to
overhaul the Obilic unit, which failed Tuesday. But that doesn't
solve the immediate problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''Due to neglect of 10 or more years, if the whole system breaks
down, it takes a while to repair them,'' Lindmeier said.
</P>
<P>
   That is small comfort to the people of Kosovo, who -- right or
wrong -- expected everything to work once the United Nations and
NATO took over.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, when heat, electricity and water failed,
international agencies assured the public that things would get
better in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are all frustrated,'' said U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes.
''We're having a difficult time. It was a very cold winter,
unfortunately it is a very hot period in the summer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
