<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Power Play Gets Mixed Results  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW KRAMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Vladimir Putin won a battle in the lower
house of parliament and lost one in the upper house Friday in his
ambitious bid to strengthen his powers over Russia's regional
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The lower house, called the State Duma, voted 335 to 27 to
approve a law allowing Putin to fire local officials and mayors.
Three lawmakers abstained.
</P>
<P>
   The upper house, meanwhile, vetoed a bill that would let the
president dismiss governors who violate laws. The upper house,
called the Federation Council, is composed of regional governors
whose powers are threatened by Putin's plan. The vote was 83 to 16
against the bill, with nine abstentions.
</P>
<P>
   The measures were two of three draft laws Putin has proposed to
rein in the powers of provincial governors, who in recent years
have assumed wide authority -- in some cases nearly total -- in their
remote regions of the vast country. Wealthier regions are reluctant
to share revenues with the federal government, and some regional
leaders have suppressed dissent and independent media.
</P>
<P>
   The president describes his package of bills as a bid to force
regional bosses to comply with the country's 1993 constitution, but
critics say he is eliminating checks and balances on the
president's power.
</P>
<P>
   The Federation Council last week rejected the third measure,
which would have replaced governors in the upper chamber with
appointed senators. On Friday the upper house agreed to form a
joint commission with the Duma to work out a compromise on that
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Duma voted Friday to accept this offer. If the compromise
fails the Duma can attempt to override the Federation Council's
veto with a two-thirds majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   The bills have driven a wedge between the two houses of
parliament. Their rocky road through the legislature has been the
first serious political blow to Putin, who was elected March 26 and
has vowed to bring order to Russia's unwieldy state machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Putin says that up to one-fifth of local laws contradict the
federal constitution. He says tightening control over the regions
is essential to dealing with Russia's economic problems and keeping
the country from falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   The law passed by the Duma on Friday lets Putin fire mayors and
district chiefs who, according to court rulings, have violated
federal laws. He could also dismiss local legislatures, but only
after a two-thirds vote by the Duma.
</P>
<P>
   Putin offered a consolation in the bill to the regional
governors whose powers he is trying to trim: The law gives
governors the right to dismiss mayors and local officials if courts
find they have violated the law.
</P>
<P>
   The bill now goes to the Federation Council, which is unlikely
to look favorably on these measures either, analysts have said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 1333 </TRAILER>
