<HEADLINE> Chagall Exhibit Opens in Belarus  </HEADLINE>
By MARINA BABKINA
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINSK, Belarus (AP) -- An exhibit of artist Marc Chagall's
sketches went on display Friday in Belarus, offering viewers a rare
glimpse of their native son's vast work as an artist in exile.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Belarusian landscape and provincial traditions
inspired Chagall throughout his life, none of the former Soviet
republic's museums display work by the world-renowned artist.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit in the capital Minsk, marking the 113th anniversary
of Chagall's birth Friday, is only the second time his works have
come to Belarus since he emigrated to France in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Soviet authorities frowned on Chagall for having fled the
country, but many people in Belarus now mention him as one of the
country's most illustrious natives.
</P>
<P>
   The works on display at Minsk's National Art Museum included 20
sketches for a job he took in 1964 decorating the ceiling of the
Paris Opera house and 10 lithographs with scenes from that city in
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The pastels, gouaches and ink drawings on display through August
at the National Art Museum are being shown for their first time in
Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   Chagall's granddaughters and a great-granddaughter unveiled the
works. Exhibit organizers included the French Foreign Ministry and
the Belarusian Culture Ministry. The last time Chagall's works
showed in Belarus was in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Chagall left the Soviet Union in 1922 after briefly embracing
the Communist ideals of the Bolshevik revolution, and spent the
rest of his life in exile in Paris and then the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Scenes from his hometown of Vitebsk northeast of Minsk served as
a recurring theme in Chagall's art until his death in 1985.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
