<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Accused General Will Retire  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The two-star general accused of sexually
harassing the Army's highest-ranking woman has asked to retire,
officials said Friday. The move apparently closes a case that drew
widespread attention and already cost Maj. Gen. Larry Smith an
appointment to be the Army's deputy inspector general.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was given a written reprimand for conduct unbecoming an
officer and for sexually harassing an officer. He has submitted his
request to retire Sept. 1, Army spokesman Col. Edwin Veiga said.
Officials said it was likely the request would be approved.
</P>
<P>
   The general denied any wrongdoing in a brief statement issued by
the Army on his behalf, his first public comment on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, for the good of my family and the Army, we have
elected to put it behind us and move on with our lives,'' he said,
making no explicit mention of the alleged offense nor his intention
to retire.
</P>
<P>
   His accuser, Lt. Gen. Claudia Kennedy, said: ''I am satisfied
with the Army's action in this case. As far as I am concerned, this
matter is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army's announcement marked the first time it publicly
acknowledged that Kennedy made an accusation and that Smith was the
accused officer. Kennedy, a three-star general, outranked Smith. In
May, officials privately acknowledged that Army inspector general
Lt. Gen. Michael Ackerman had substantiated Kennedy's allegation,
but no details were offered.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a Freedom of Information Act request, the Army
released a sanitized copy of the inspector general's report Friday.
It said it had substantiated two allegations: that Smith
''improperly displayed disrespect toward a commissioned officer ...
by holding her and kissing her against her will,'' and that he had
''improperly sexually harassed'' Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   There were no witnesses to the incident, which was said to have
occurred in Kennedy's Pentagon office in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Smith and Kennedy were in ''total disagreement''
about what happened in her office that day.
</P>
<P>
   Smith told investigators he had hugged Kennedy and possibly
given her a ''cheek kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He denied anything beyond that happened,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy told investigators he grabbed her, held her against her
will and kissed her.
</P>
<P>
   Smith provided 52 character witnesses in his defense, seven of
whom were interviewed by the inspector general's office. Six others
who had served with Smith also were interviewed. None said they
knew of any prior misconduct by Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general concluded Smith was a ''highly respected
officer and gentleman with an unblemished career.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it found that Kennedy's credibility was a decisive
factor. She had no motive for making a false allegation against
Smith, the report said, and the two generals were not in
competition for the same job.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who is married, began his Army career in 1966 as a second
lieutenant and served three tours of duty in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement announcing the outcome, the Army said Smith had
been given an ''administrative memorandum of reprimand'' on
Wednesday by Gen. John Keane, the vice chief of staff who reviewed
the inspector general's finding.
</P>
<P>
   The Army saw no basis for a criminal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, the Army announced that Smith was to become deputy
inspector general, a move that spurred Kennedy two months later to
tell superiors about the alleged incident.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's job changed was suspended in November and quietly
rescinded in May. Since November, he has worked as a special
assistant to the Army Materiel Command's commanding general.
</P>
<P>
   At a retirement ceremony June 2 -- 31 years to the day after she
entered the Army -- Kennedy said the institution she grew up with
has made ''measured and steady'' progress toward fairer treatment
of female soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our Army is filled with women and men who care and who are in
a position to change and improve the conditions under which we
serve,'' Kennedy said then. ''Today, more than ever, women are a
powerful force'' in the U.S. military, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said she had more than fulfilled the aspirations she
held when she was commissioned a second lieutenant on June 2, 1969
-- at a time when women served in a separate Women's Army Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've risen further than I ever dared to hope,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy had served since May 1997 as the Army's deputy chief of
staff for intelligence. With her departure, the Army has no
three-star female generals.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that since she entered the Army, thousands of
positions once held exclusively by men have been opened to women,
and she said of the Army's male-dominated culture: ''It is
responsive, it is changing, and it is highly accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The change has been measured and steady,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although she has left her Pentagon post, Kennedy's official
retirement date is Aug. 1. Her departure plans were set before her
sexual harassment case became public in March.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon statement: http://www.dtic.mil/armylink
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
