<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope's Prison Visit Raising Hopes  </HEADLINE>
By ALESSANDRA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- With tensions rising in Italy's overcrowded prisons
and politicians debating what to do about it, Pope John Paul II's
planned visit to a prison in Rome is raising some prisoners'
expectations of a long-awaited amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul will celebrate Mass on Sunday inside Regina Coeli, a
prison in a 17th-century building that once housed a monastery.
Nine inmates will serve as altar boys and 14 others will make up
the choir.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled two-hour visit is part of the pontiff's Holy Year
activities. It follows his recent call for governments worldwide to
make a ''gesture of clemency'' to inmates.
</P>
<P>
   In his June 30 message, the pope urged a ''reduction, even a
modest one, of the term of punishment'' as a ''clear sign of
sensitivity to their condition.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask His Holiness to let a bit of hope and faith enter
through these walls,'' said Domenico Franceschetti, a Regina Coeli
inmate, in a letter published Friday in the newspaper Il
Messaggero.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Coeli houses 900 inmates. While prison officials would
not provide any figures on capacity, they acknowledged the facility
is overcrowded, as are the rest of Italy's 217 prisons.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 54,000 people behind bars across the country --
14,000 more than the prisons were built to hold.
</P>
<P>
   Many inmates have been staging peaceful protests recently,
asking for better living conditions. Those in Regina Coeli pounded
on their cell bars last month, while in other places prisoners set
sheets on fire or went on hunger strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Italian politicians have been debating whether to grant some
sort of amnesty to ease the overcrowding, but have failed to reach
any agreement. Such measures require a two-thirds majority to pass
in parliament, making an accord between the center-left governing
bloc and the right-wing opposition necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The government did issue a decree Friday to spend $1.2 billion
to build more prisons and add personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The decree also lets authorities immediately expel illegal
immigrants who have committed crimes punishable with up to three
years in prison if the immigrants are caught in the act and judges
uphold the arrests. That measure aims to reduce the prison
population in Italy, where many prisoners are immigrants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 1520 </TRAILER>
