<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crisis Over Orange Order March  </HEADLINE>
By SHAWN POGATCHNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Last-minute efforts to defuse
the violent confrontation over Protestant marches in Northern
Ireland crashed into a wall of harsh words and suspicions on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Portadown leader of the Orange Order brotherhood, Harold
Gracey, insisted he would not enter negotiations at all unless his
followers first are permitted to parade Sunday through the town's
main Catholic neighborhood, Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   His blunt demand -- combined with his repeated refusals to
condemn the week's violence -- undercut a new compromise-minded plan
that had been presented hours earlier in Gracey's own name, though
written by advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Breandan MacCionnaith, the former Irish Republican Army prisoner
who since 1995 has led anti-Orange protesters on Garvaghy Road,
dismissed his opponents' initiative as ''a tired old proposal from
tired old men who can't face up to the reality of what is happening
around them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orange document, presented to a government-appointed Parades
Commission, offered the prospect of opening talks with MacCionnaith
-- something the conservative fraternal group has refused for years
to do -- if the ban on passing through Garvaghy Road is lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Though some observers saw hope in this approach, militant and
moderate Catholics alike said it was an unacceptably backward way
of resolving the problem. The Parades Commission agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem lies in the sequence they seek,'' said a two-page
response from the government-appointed commission. It reiterated
that negotiations involving Orange leaders and Garvaghy Road
residents should happen ''before and lead to a parade.''
</P>
<P>
   With no solution appearing likely, British soldiers charged with
keeping the hostile camps apart on Sunday erected extensive
barbed-wire defenses in pastures near the disputed turf.
</P>
<P>
   It gave the fields the look of a World War I battlefield -- the
very event that the Orangemen say they want to commemorate this
weekend. Thousands of Northern Irish men, Protestants and Catholics
alike, died in the Battle of the Somme in 1916, but Catholics say
the modern march is designed merely to annoy them.
</P>
<P>
   This year, police also have deployed massive Belgian water
cannons against the protesters who have massed each night near the
field barricades. The joint police-army positions appear
well-prepared to repel any Protestant attempt to outflank or break
through them.
</P>
<P>
   But elsewhere, Protestant hooligans have spent the week blocking
roads, hijacking and burning vehicles, threatening isolated
Catholic areas and pelting riot police with stones, firecrackers
and gasoline bombs.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest riot statistics Friday, police said 37 officers
and two soldiers had been wounded during the course of 145 attacks
on their forces, including a dozen gun attacks. They had no
statistics on injured civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they had seized 268 gasoline bombs and arrested 55
people.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's minister for Northern Ireland, Peter Mandelson,
defended the police efforts to contain the rioters, who were left
free to block many roads.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was right that riot police were containing the
violence, but often did not ''risk their lives unnecessarily by
rushing into a crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   But Catholics accused the predominantly Protestant police force,
which is supposed to be reformed as part of the peace accord, of
not doing enough either to arrest rioters or to keep them out of
vulnerable Catholic parts of Belfast. Forty-three houses and 27
businesses, most owned or occupied by Catholics, have been attacked
in the past week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 1521 </TRAILER>
