<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Milan approved change in $215M city water contract without city, state OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - Without the knowledge of state or city
officials, Mayor Milton Milan's administration signed an agreement
with a water company, altering the largest contract in city
history, according to a published report.
</P>
<P>
   Under the original $215 million contract with Camden Water LLC
for privatization of the city's water and sewer system, Camden
would have received $20 million by the end of January 1999, when
the company took over operations. The money was to be used to
renovate the aging system and was to be repaid over 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   With the alteration, signed in December 1998 by Mayor Milan and
Preston Taylor, the city business administrator, the company was
allowed to pay once certain conditions were met, The Philadelphia
Inquirer reported in Friday's editions. Those conditions included
loans from third-party lenders. The city has not yet received the
payment.
</P>
<P>
   City Attorney John Misci said that, under the ordinance that
allowed the water contract, the administration was authorized to
make the change. The ordinance says the mayor can make
''nonmaterial'' changes to the contract.
</P>
<P>
   Misci said the alteration merely ''clarified'' the contract
language. He also said the change was needed because a lawsuit by a
group of residents could have threatened the deal. The lawsuit,
which sought to put the contract to a public vote, was dismissed
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The original contract with Camden Water LLC, a subsidiary of
Chicago-based U.S. Water, was approved by the city council in
September 1998 and by the state Financial Review Board in January
1999.
</P>
<P>
   City records show that the agreement was never sent to the city
clerk's office, where a copy of the contract is required to be
filed. State officials told the newspaper Thursday that they were
not aware of the change.
</P>
<P>
   The change was not included in a lawsuit filed by the city last
year against Camden Water LLC and U.S. Water demanding payment of
the $20 million. It was in response to the city's lawsuit that
Camden Water gave the court a copy of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   David A. Speziali, the lawyer representing Camden Water in the
lawsuit, said he did not know why the city did not include the
agreement in its lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I assumed that it was just an oversight,'' he told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Speziali said he agreed with the city that the alteration did
not make material changes to the contract. He also said the company
and the city are still trying to work out how and when the $20
million would be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Ali Sloan El, who opposed the privatization deal,
said members of Milan's administration ''need to be locked up, and
the key or the latch or the lock needs to be permanently sealed.
They deserve no sunlight,'' he told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he did not remember signing the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't remember some of the stuff I signed last week, because
I sign so many documents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A call to Milan's office Friday was not immediately returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
