<HEADLINE> Croatian Court Acquits Five Serbs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- A court on Friday overturned war crimes
convictions against five Croation Serbs, saying no evidence at
their original trial linked them to attacks on Croatian cities in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   The five were first convicted in 1995 and that verdict was
upheld in 1999. They had received setnences ranging from eight to
15 years for the shelling of Croatia's eastern region during the
country's civil war. The men were held responsible for killing 10
people and wounding 30 others, state-run HINA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   But the verdict was annulled by the Supreme Court last year and
the case was sent back to the court in Osijek, 145 miles east of
Zagreb.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign observers, who have monitored the case since 1995, had
criticized both earlier verdicts, charging that the proceedings
might have been part of a campaign of vengeance against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the country's minority Serbs took up arms against
Croatia's secession from the former Yugoslavia. The Serbs then
seized a third of the country which Zagreb recaptured in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The five, who surrendered to Croatian authorities in 1998,
reiterated their innocence Friday and expressed regret for the
victims, state-run news agency HINA reported.
</P>
<P>
   Since a new, pro-Western government took power in January,
succeeding late President Franjo Tudjman's party, anti-Serb
sentiments have ebbed. The new government is eager to prove that
its courts are just and harbor no anti-Serb biases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
