<HEADLINE> Mexico Granted Most U.S. Visas  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP)-- The State Department, responding to a proposal
for a large increase in the number of U.S. immigrant visas for
Mexicans, said Friday the 75,000 granted to Mexicans in the last
fiscal year was the highest total worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was contained in a working paper obtained by the
Wall Street Journal from the campaign of President-elect Vicente
Fox, who will take office on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The document said a sharp increase in the number of U.S. visas
will be a foreign policy priority of Fox. A Fox policy adviser told
the Journal it would be good for Mexico if the U.S. permitted the
migration of 250,000 Mexicans a year.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher noted that U.S. law
bars any one country from receiving more than 7 percent of the
worldwide total of immigrant visas.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last fiscal year, the per-country limit was 27,083 visas for
one country, and Mexicans received all 27,083 visas that they were
allowed,'' Boucher said. When spouses and children were added, the
figure for Mexico on immigrant visas was 75,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any special provisions going beyond these normal rules and
calculations would require congressional action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of illegal migrants entering the country is believed
to be about 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said the administration agrees with Fox's statements
during the campaign that economic development in Mexico is a
long-range solution to the migration problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''We look forward to working with him on the migration issue
which is very important to both of us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
