<HEADLINE> Report: Rosie Perez refuses to visit estranged, dying mom  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Actress Rosie Perez, an outspoken AIDS activist,
has recently refused to visit her estranged mother, who is dying of
the disease, according to a report published Friday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Perez bristled at any suggestion that she had neglected
her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ''While it is accurate to say she is not the woman who raised me
and we are somewhat estranged, I have always wished for her the
best of health and continue to offer my support in that regard,''
Perez said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a strong AIDS activist, I have pleaded with my mother to
accept my assistance through whatever connections I may have within
the AIDS community; she has refused it,'' Perez said. ''I have also
offered her financial assistance, which was accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News reported that Lydia Perez has suffered from AIDS
for six years and is now near death.
</P>
<P>
   It quoted an unidentified nurse attending Lydia Perez as saying
that Rosie Perez last visited her mother on New Year's Day, when
she brought her a hamburger and fries from McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   Lydia Perez told News columnist Juan Gonzalez that her famous
daughter's last visit before that was ''a couple of years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Please tell her I'm dying and I just want to see her one more
time,'' the mother told Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, the star of movies including ''Do the Right Thing'' and
''White Men Can't Jump,'' has been active in the fight against
AIDS, raising money for AIDS research and counseling young people
to guard against HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Johnson, associate executive director of the AIDS-service
group Gay Men's Health Crisis, released a statement saying that the
organization ''can confirm that Rosie Perez was personally involved
in seeking direct services for her mother at GMHC. It was our
understanding at the time that her mother declined to use our
services for personal reasons. Referrals to other agencies were
provided.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News story notes that Rosie Perez was one of 10
children born to Lydia Perez and that she spent several years in
group foster homes because her mother, who suffered from mental
illness, could not handle raising them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
