<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Conservatives Seek Leader  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- For the second time in two weeks, members of a
new conservative party vote Saturday for a leader in their effort
to unify Canada's political right and take on the governing Liberal
Party.
</P>
<P>
   The contest between former Alberta Treasurer Stockwell Day and
opposition leader Preston Manning will determine who becomes the
main challenger for the prime minister's office occupied since 1993
by Liberal leader Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
   Day won 44 percent in the first round of voting June 24 and
Manning got 36 percent. More than 200,000 members of the Canadian
Alliance are eligible to vote in Saturday's runoff.
</P>
<P>
   The party formed in March out of Manning's old Reform Party,
which had a base of support confined to Canada's western provinces.
Now the Alliance is the nation's largest party, based on
membership, but whether that growth can translate into nationwide
support in a federal election remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Chretien, who must call an election by the end of 2001, has
dismissed the Alliance as little more than a repackaged version of
the Reform Party, which failed to win a single seat in Parliament
east of Manitoba in the 1997 election.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, 58, who led the Reform Party's rise from a western
protest movement in 1987 into the official Parliament opposition,
engineered the creation of the Canadian Alliance to stop
vote-splitting on the right by attracting traditional supporters of
the Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between Manning and Day, 49, are more style than
substance. Both come from Alberta, both have been preachers, and
both espouse strongly conservative economic principles. In
addition, both men are considered social conservatives who oppose
abortion, want tougher penalties for criminals and more controls on
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Day, however, has a reputation for bluntness on social issues
that Manning warns will harm the Alliance's chances of forming a
nationwide conservative movement in the same way divisions over
issues such as abortion have divided U.S. conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Party acknowledges the outcome of Saturday's vote
will affect its strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've become comfortable with Preston Manning, we know Preston
Manning and we know how to deal with Preston Manning,'' Liberal
Party president Stephen LeDrew said. ''Stockwell Day, there's no
question, is a new person. We're going to have to reassess his
program, his campaign and we're going to have to adjust.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
