<HEADLINE> Farm workers appear in court for co-worker's slaying  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAYS LANDING, N.J. (AP) - A migrant farm worker charged in the
slaying of a co-worker called the accusations ''lies'' Friday when
he went before a judge.
</P>
<P>
   ''What has been said, it's all lies,'' Ruperto Hernandez, 35,
told Superior Court Judge Manuel Greenberg. ''There's some mistake
about what the police are saying,'' he said, through interpreter
Carmen Sacco.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, 23-year-old Javier S. Vasquez and Martin A. Madera,
27, who live at Buena Vista Farms in Vineland, are each charged
with murder and conspiracy to commit murder.
</P>
<P>
   Vasquez also is charged with aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Vasquez got into a fight with Gaspar Leon, 34,
in a bunkhouse at the farm and hit him over the head with a bottle.
The three then took Leon to a rural roadside, where Hernandez and
Madera held Leon down as Vasquez slit his throat, according to
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez allegedly held Leon's head up so Vasquez could slash
his throat; Madera used his foot to held Leon down, according to a
criminal complaint read in court Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The three, who are Mexican nationals, were being held on
$250,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic County Prosecutor Jeffrey Blitz said Vasquez slashed
Leon's throat with a parsley knife before abandoning the body in
woods off Jackson Road in Buena Vista Township, where a passing
motorist found it Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   No motive has been given for the killing. Assistant Atlantic
County Prosecutor Murray Talasnik would not comment on it Friday,
nor would he say what evidence led police to the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   No decision has been made about whether to seek the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   None of the suspects were represented by lawyers at their
appearances before Greenberg. Each asked for court-appointed
lawyers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
