<HEADLINE> Clinton To Appear Before Okinawans  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Japanese anger over criminal and unruly
behavior by U.S. soldiers could overshadow global economic issues
when President Clinton joins a summit of world leaders on Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   A Marine corporal stands accused of fondling a junior high
schoolgirl in the latest incident in years of trouble between local
residents and U.S. troops based in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Friday that Clinton plans a speech to
residents at Okinawa's Peace Park upon his arrival for the July
20-23 summit as well as meetings with community leaders. It will be
the first visit of a U.S. President to the island where 26,000 U.S.
troops are stationed. In all, Japan hosts 47,000 U.S. military
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman P. J. Crowley said Clinton would be prepared to deal
with the issue of complaints against U.S. troops when he attends
the July 21-23 Group of Eight summit on Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something we view very seriously, and the military
command is working closely with local leaders'' on the
investigation of U.S. soldiers' conduct, Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps on Friday imposed a strict curfew and added a
ban on liquor and civilian dress for corps members. A broader U.S.
military curfew in effect since 1995 when three servicemen were
convicted of raping a 12-year-old Okinawa girl had been lifted only
last October.
</P>
<P>
   The new midnight-7:30 a.m. curfew, applying only to Marines,
followed arrest of a 19-year-old Marine lance corporal who was
charged by local police with ''indecency and unlawful entry.'' The
mother of a junior high school student told police she found the
soldier drunk and half-naked, on top of the girl, kissing and
fondling her as she screamed.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's ambassador to Washington, Shunji Yanai, said the
Japanese government is concerned over the incident and supports the
idea of Clinton having ''contact with the local people'' during the
July 21-23 G-8 summit with leaders of Japan, the United States,
Canada, Britain, Germany, Japan, Italy and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is really an unfortunate incident. And I hope that it will
not affect the environment of the G-8 summit,'' the ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   He said the summit is intended to focus on greater global
prosperity, including the spread of information technology, social
development and debt relief for developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the concerns of local residents over the U.S. military
presence and a continuation of recent demonstrations that could
detract from the summit theme, Yanai said Clinton is expected to
get a good reception on Okinawa.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be a wonderful occasion for the U.S. president to
address the local people, who host many U.S. military bases,''
Yanai said.
</P>
<P>
   Another U.S. action that has added to tension between Americans
and Okinawans before the summit is cancellation of plans for
Secretary of State Madeleine Alright to attend a July 12-13 foreign
ministers meeting ahead of the G-8 sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Miyazaki City, where she was to dedicate a 500-seat school
auditorium, reacted by reversing a decision to name the auditorium
for Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Yanai said, however, that Japanese leaders understand her need
to handle the Mideast peace summit beginning at Camp David, Md.,
next week.
</P>
<P>
   The White House stressed that Clinton, who is also participating
in the Mideast talks, would attend the Okinawa summit.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   G-8 Summit site: http://www.summit-okinawa.gr.jp
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military posts on Okinawa:
http://www.virtualokinawa.com/military/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
