<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Jaws' Author Seeks To Help Sharks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- ''Jaws'' author Peter Benchley joined a
conservation group in calling for an end to industrial practices
that kill more than 100 million sharks and shark-like fish annually
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that we have the right to extinguish any
species,'' said Benchley, whose best-selling 1974 book was about a
man-eating shark.
</P>
<P>
   According to the San Francisco-based organization WildAid, 90
percent of some species have been killed by crews seeking only fins
and fishing techniques in which sharks are caught on multiple hooks
dangling from 50-mile lines.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, the group said an average of 12 people are killed
by sharks annually.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sharks are more often the victims than the villains,'' WildAid
director Peter Knights said.
</P>
<P>
   Benchley and Knights will take their campaign to Asia, where
there is demand for shark fin soup, considered a delicacy. The tour
coincides with the 25th anniversary of the Steven Spielberg film
based on Benchley's book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
