<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Owner of Babe Ruth-autographed baseball found before state auctioned it </HEADLINE>
By LEE UEHARA
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH (AP) - The state was ready to showcase a baseball
autographed by the ''Sultan of Swat,'' Babe Ruth, at its unclaimed
property auction when to the surprise of organizers, they found the
owner.
</P>
<P>
   After trying to track down the owner for close to a year, Deputy
State Treasurer Charles Heatherly said Friday he located her.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Ann Prall of Charlotte also learned she now is the proud
owner of a baseball autographed by Hank Aaron, savings bonds and
some coins.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a happy ending to this story,'' Heatherly said.
</P>
<P>
   Prall did not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Heatherly said the baseball and other items were in a safe
deposit box with an unpaid balance of $270. The bank sent it to the
state for its annual unclaimed property auction, scheduled July 15.
</P>
<P>
   The state sent the baseball to an expert, who verified it was
the real thing, Heatherly said. The baseball was estimated to be
worth between $3,200 to $7,500, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the state didn't receive bids near $7,500, it was going to
try auctioning it on eBay or sending it to Christie's or Sotheby's
in New York, Heatherly said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But, this is the whole purpose of the program, to find the
owners of unclaimed property,'' Heatherly said.
</P>
<P>
   Every year the state treasury department gets unclaimed property
in a myriad of forms, including savings accounts, stocks, safe
deposit box contents, jewelry and electronics. The goods are
collected from banks, hospitals and occasionally public places such
as malls and airports.
</P>
<P>
   The state tries to find the property's owners by publishing
advertisements in newspapers, making radio broadcasts and sending
lists to clerks of court statewide, said Regina Morgan, operations
manager for the state treasury department.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll have a booth set up so people at the auction can check
to see if they have any unclaimed property,'' Morgan said. If all
attempts fail at locating property owners, the items are put up for
auction.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the state collected $32.6 million worth of unclaimed
property, most in the form of savings accounts, stocks and bonds.
Only tangible property - items such as the baseballs - is
auctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds from the auction, estimated at $30,000 for this year,
go to the North Carolina State Education Assistance Authority for
student loans to the state's public universities. Last year, 5,316
loans were made to students.
</P>
<P>
   The 263 items at this year's auction also include a signed
baseball from Jim ''Catfish'' Hunter, gold coins, U.S. and foreign
currency, jewelry and electronics. The auction at the State
Fairgrounds is expected to draw 500 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-07-00 1714 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000707.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Mulls New EPA Guidelines  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite a congressional demand to delay
action, the Clinton administration is considering imposing new
pollution controls to clean up thousands of lakes and streams --
worrying Democrats about the potential political fallout.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation, close to being issued by the Environmental
Protection Agency would create new requirements for farmers,
businesses, industrial plants and utilities in areas where water
quality does not meet federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   As much as 20,000 impaired lakes and streams -- 40 percent of the
nation's waterways -- would be affected. Critics call it an
unprecedented and costly move by the federal government to deal
with farm and industrial runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Critics such as farm groups, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and
many governors have focused intense lobbying against the proposal.
They want the administration to abandon the idea, or at least
postpone it until its cost can be more closely examined. They say
the cost could go as high as $2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   EPA Administrator Carol Browner has argued that the new rule
will cost less than $100 million annually. She said the regulation
is necessary to address some of the country's worst water pollution
problems, which have left many lakes and streams unsuitable for
fishing or swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, opponents attached to a high-priority spending bill
a rider directing the EPA to delay a decision for a year. The bill
has not been signed by President Clinton and the administration has
not ruled out issuing the new regulation before the bill becomes
law.
</P>
<P>
   Recent days have seen intense discussions at the White House
about the issue, with Browner arguing for going ahead with the
rule, said one administration source, who spoke on condition of not
being identified.
</P>
<P>
   Another administration source said the possibility remains that
Clinton would push out the new rule before signing the spending
bill, despite the possibility of a political backlash on both
Capitol Hill and the presidential campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a stick in the eye to Congress,'' says Bill Kovacs,
director of environmental affairs at the Chamber of Commerce, which
lobbied aggressively against the EPA rule.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., accused the White House of
circumventing Congress, which he said made clear it doesn't want
the new regulation imposed this year. Farm-state Democrats joined
Republicans in denouncing the new rules at a hearing last month.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, some in administration officials are concerned the
rules' passing could cause fallout in key Midwest states for Vice
President Al Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee,
who also supports the regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Among those complaining to Clinton about the regulation's
''major financial burden'' was Iowa Gov. Thomas Vilsack, who has
been mentioned as a possible Gore running mate.
</P>
<P>
   The regulation, formally known as the Total Maximum Daily Load
(TMDL) program, would give states 15 years to develop plans to
clean up waterways that do not meet federal water quality
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Landowners involved in agriculture for the first time would have
to comply with pollution discharge permits if they contribute to
nearby water quality problems. Industrial plants, utilities and
factories, which already must comply with pollution permits, fear
they will be subject to even tighter discharge requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rules are going to force the states to set limits that are
not well thought out,'' said Paul Bailey, an official of the Edison
Electric Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But Ed Hopkins of the Sierra Club said new efforts to address
pollution into waterways is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we're to continue to make progress we're going to have to
address runoff from agriculture and forests and construction sites
and those other sources of pollution,'' Hopkins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 1717 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
