<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safe Haven bill signed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Mothers who otherwise might endanger or
kill their newborns now have a humane alternative: dropping them
off at a ''safe haven,'' no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, acting as governor, signed the
bill into law Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the measure, it's unlikely that parents who safely deliver
an unwanted child to a hospital or police station would be
prosecuted. Instead, they could simply leave an infant younger than
30 days old and walk away.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, a parent could be charged with endangering the
welfare of a child, a second-degree offense that carries a penalty
of up to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The bill does not offer blanket immunity from prosecution,
however. Parents who harm a child could still be charged
criminally.
</P>
<P>
   The measure earmarks $500,000 for a 24-hour hot line where
callers could get information about the Safe Haven law and
adoption. It also calls for a public education campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, who signed the bill at St. Joseph's Hospital and
Medical Center in Paterson, said it is designed to save lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want individuals, who for whatever reasons feel they cannot
care for their newborn infants, to leave the babies at a safe haven
such as a hospital or police station where the children can receive
the medical attention and care they need to survive,'' he said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Collins served as acting governor because Gov. Christie Whitman
and Senate President Donald DiFrancesco, who is next in the line of
succession, were both out of state Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, people dropping off infants can remain
anonymous and do not have to provide any background or medical
information about themselves or the child.
</P>
<P>
   The state, after ensuring the child does not require medical
care, will place the infant in foster care while officials
terminate parental rights.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, five babies have been abandoned in New Jersey.
One of them, a newborn boy found lying amid litter near Paterson
railroad tracks, later died.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best-known case of fatal child abandonment was the
infant who died in 1996 after North Jersey teen couple Amy
Grossberg and Brian Peterson threw him into a trash bin outside a
Delaware motel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-07-00 1719 </TRAILER>
