<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoons Kill 16 in Western Pacific  </HEADLINE>
By KOZO MIZOGUCHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Typhoons in the western Pacific unleashed deadly
floods, landslides and tornadoes in the Philippines on Friday, and
one threatened to strike Tokyo next.
</P>
<P>
   At least 16 people died and 10 were missing as a pair of
typhoons converged on the Philippines, bringing torrential rains
that forced 400,000 to flee their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Schools and municipal buildings were overwhelmed by the
homeless, who are likely to need shelter for up to a week, said
James Sian, manager of national disaster relief in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   ''It isn't far-fetched to say that our supplies will run out,''
Sian said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the storms was moving northeast at 25 miles per hour,
away from the Philippines but directly toward the heavily populated
coastal areas around Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Meteorological Agency forecast that Typhoon Kirogi, with
sustained winds of 78 miles per hour, will reach land by Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a typhoon scored a direct hit on the Japanese
capital was in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Waves up to 13 feet high could slap the coast, and up to 10
inches of rain could fall in the Tokyo area through Saturday,
causing flooding and landslides, forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   The typhoon's approach prompted Japan's three major airlines to
cancel at least 50 domestic flights in and out of Tokyo on
Saturday, Kyodo News agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   On the island of Kozushima southeast of Tokyo, which stands
directly in the storm's path, 788 residents fled to a school on
higher ground, said Yutaka Shimizu, a local government official.
</P>
<P>
   The other storm off the Philippines, Typhoon Kai-tak, was about
375 miles southeast of Hong Kong at 9 p.m. Friday local time and
expected to remain nearly stationary overnight, the Hong Kong
Observatory said.
</P>
<P>
   A third typhoon formed Friday in the South China Sea from a
tropical storm and was tracked heading for mainland China,
meteorologists said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Meteorological Agency: http://www.kishou.go.jp
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong Observatory: http://www.info.gov.hk/hko/ and
http://www.weather.gov.hk/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
