<HEADLINE> Harry Potter's magic working magic on magic  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Harry Potter is working magic on magicians,
who are thrilled to see little imaginations embracing the fictional
tyke's world of special powers.
</P>
<P>
   With television and the Web exposing tricks of the trade like
never before, the young orphan with magical skills is a reminder of
what makes magic so - magical, members of the International
Brotherhood of Magicians said at their annual convention Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all the exposure and everybody on the Internet wanting to
find out how things are done, so little is done to spark the
imagination and joy in children,'' said Abb Dickson, a past
president of the brotherhood. ''That's what the Harry Potter series
does. You can pretend once more and believe once more.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Harry Potter has done so much for magic,'' said Dickson,
president of the World Alliance of Magicians.
</P>
<P>
   The merchandising that is sure to follow from the astounding
success of J.K. Rowling's series will only further advance the
craft, dealers demonstrating their wares at the convention said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll see Harry Potter magic sets, Harry Potter magic books
and that will have a profound effect,'' said Richard Kaufman,
editor and publisher of Genii magazine. ''Anything that makes
little new magicians is good for magic.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth book in the Harry Potter series, ''Harry Potter and
the Goblet of Fire,'' was being released at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Long before there was Harry Potter's goblet, there was Harry
Houdini's Chinese water torture cell. But even Houdini's niece
recognizes the appeal of the younger Harry. While Marie Blood's
taste in mysteries runs more toward Perry Mason, ''I am waiting to
see it,'' she said of the latest Harry Potter book while signing
autographs after regaling an audience with tales of her famous
uncle. The escape artist died in 1926, when she was 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter was not far from the thoughts of 7-year-old Ariel
Chaudhuri and her mother, Gretchen, at the convention. Ariel is on
her second adventure and looking forward to others.
</P>
<P>
   ''We saw an act the other night, a magician who used bubbles,
and thought he would be a perfect Harry Potter character,''
Gretchen Chaudhuri said. ''He acted just like Harry Potter would.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
