<HEADLINE> Teen-ager's death appears to be isolated case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The death of a 17-year-old from bacterial
meningitis last Saturday appears to be an isolated case, Gloucester
County health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Deptford Township High School student, whose name was not
released, first became ill last Friday night while visiting in Cape
May County.
</P>
<P>
   Friends took her to Burdette Tomlin Memorial Hospital in Cape
May Courthouse last Saturday. She was transferred to Children's
Hospital of Philadelphia, where she later died, according to Louis
Lamanna, Cape May County health officer and public health
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   While it's unknown how the girl contracted the disease, health
officials said no other cases were reported in the county or
surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
   The case was first reported in Cape May County, but Gloucester
County health officials are handling the investigation since that
is where the girl lived.
</P>
<P>
   Although she attended summer school at Deptford, it's unlikely
classmates were exposed to the bacteria because no classes were
scheduled during the Fourth of July holiday, Chad Bruner,
Gloucester County health department director, told the Philadelphia
Inquirer in Friday's editions. As a precaution, the teen-ager's
friends and family were treated with antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Bacterial meningitis strikes the brain and spinal membranes and
can be cured if treated early. Symptoms, which include high fever,
vomiting, severe headaches and stiff neck, may not appear for 10
days after exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Most people often don't realize they have been infected until
they are sick.
</P>
<P>
   ''It just sneaks up on you,'' Bruner said.
</P>
<P>
   Meningitis is spread through close contact with infected
individuals. Anyone who suspects they have been exposed to the
disease should seek medical assistance immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
