<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NY Times To Debut Kids' Book List  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Times Book Review will start a
best-seller list for children's books on July 23.
</P>
<P>
   The list of 15 best sellers will include all categories of
children's hardcover books, including fiction and nonfiction,
picture books and ''chapter'' books, those that are longer and have
more text, the Times said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It joins the Book Review's best-seller lists for fiction,
nonfiction, ''advice, how-to and miscellaneous'' and separate lists
for paperbacks in those categories.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sales and popularity of children's books can rival and, in
the case of the Harry Potter books, even exceed those of adult
books,'' noted Charles McGrath, editor of the Book Review, which
appears each Sunday. ''With a separate children's list we can more
fully represent what people are reading, and we can clear more room
on the adult list for adult books.''
</P>
<P>
   One or more of the three books in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter
series have commanded spots on the adult fiction best-seller list
for 81 weeks to date.
</P>
<P>
   The children's list will be derived from the same sources as the
adult list, including a sample drawn from 4,000 bookstores and
wholesalers that sell to some 50,000 outlets. Sales from children's
bookstores will also soon be factored into the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The Book Review's best-seller list pages will be redesigned,
putting the new children's list in the place of the ''advice and
how-to'' hardcover list below the adult hardcover list. ''Advice
and how-to'' will move to the paperback best-seller page.
</P>
<P>
   An extended children's best-seller list will eventually be
available on the Internet at NYTimes.com. The Web site also
publishes the top 35 books in adult hardcover and paperback fiction
and nonfiction and the top 15 ''advice and how-to'' titles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
