<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York congressman uses clout to fight for extradition of fugitives </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - A New York congressman is flexing the nation's
financial muscle in hopes of forcing the Dominican Republic to
extradite two fugitives wanted for murder.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Benjamin Gilman, who heads the International Relations
Committee, is barring the transfer of a $3 million U.S. ship to the
impoverished Caribbean island over its refusal to hand over Pablo
Almonte, a man wanted for the 1988 slaying of a New York City cop.
The U.S. Defense Security Cooperation Agency was to transfer the
ship - a Balsam Class buoy tender - to Dominican officials this
month before Gilman put a halt to the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman, R-Middletown, had previously blocked millions
of dollars in humanitarian aid from reaching the Dominican Republic
because it has failed to extradite Carlos Grullon, charged with
killing his wife at the Tarrytown Hilton in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite promises from the Dominican Republic we haven't seen
any action,'' Gilman said in an interview Friday. ''As far as I'm
concerned we shouldn't be providing them with things like aid while
they harbor criminals wanted for the murder of constituents of
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilman said he only resorted to withholding aid after years of
fruitless diplomatic talks.
</P>
<P>
   While Congress routinely blocks aid, it is rare for a single
lawmaker to do so to get a criminal extradited, Gilman's spokesman
Lester Munson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman is one of only four U.S. lawmakers that have the power to
freeze foreign aid. The others are the chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee - Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina -
as well as the heads of the Senate and House subcommittees on
foreign aid appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   The Dominican Embassy had no immediate response Friday to
Gilman's actions.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Police Officer Michael Buczek, 24, was gunned down
in 1988 in the city's Washington Heights neighborhood after he and
his partner chased several people suspected of drug dealing from
the lobby of a building. After the shooting, Almonte - also known
as Pablo Almonte Lluberes - and another suspect, Daniel Mirambeaux,
fled to the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Mirambeaux was apprehended in Santo Domingo, the Dominican
capital, but leapt to his death before he could be extradited to
New York to face a first-degree murder charge, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Almonte has been indicted in absentia on a charge of
second-degree murder by the Manhattan District Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Almonte is the brother of a high-ranking Dominican police
official, Munson said. He has never been found.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case Gilman is pushing, Grullon was indicted by a
grand jury in Westchester County in December 1991 on charges he
killed his estranged wife, Yolina Camacaho. Police say Grullon shot
Camacho in front of several witnesses, including the couple's two
young children in the basement of the Hilton. Camacho worked there
as a housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Grullon also fled to the Dominican Republic. He was arrested and
spent several months in jail there before being released on bail.
He hasn't been seen since.
</P>
<P>
   A Dominican court has tried and convicted Grullon in absentia
for the murder and his bail violation, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly $6 million in aid money Gilman blocked is intended
for programs to further democracy and human rights. At the request
of the Dominican government, Gilman did allow $1.5 million for AIDS
prevention and the presidential election to go to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Donald McHenry, a professor at Georgetown University's School of
Foreign Service who specializes in developing countries, said the
practice of unilaterally blocking foreign aid is becoming more
common in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''The danger is you have 535 secretaries of state each making
decisions based on the individual needs of their constituents,''
McHenry said. ''It's not the best way to run foreign policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
