<HEADLINE> OSHA cites construction company for accident that killed two  </HEADLINE>
dshofonssy
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILFORD, Conn. (AP) - The federal government Friday cited a
construction company in the collapse of a steel structure that
killed two workers and injured two others.
</P>
<P>
   The Occupational Health and Safety Administration said Black &AMP;
Veatch did not follow established procedures to erect the steel
structure. OSHA proposed a $7,000 fine against the company.
</P>
<P>
   The structure was meant to house a steam generator for a power
plant. It collapsed in February and took down a nearby crane,
killing boilermakers Kevin Winslow, 43, of Newington, and Wayne
Most, 38, of West Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Crane operator Robert Fitch, of North Branford, was trapped in
the rubble for eight hours and lost a leg. George Scrivner of East
Haddam also was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators found that a diagonal brace on the
structure was prematurely removed, leaving the structure vulnerable
to collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ''If proper erection procedures had been adhered to, this
structure would not have collapsed,'' said Clifford Weston, OSHA's
area director.
</P>
<P>
   Black &AMP; Veatch officials have not yet received the full OSHA
report at their Kansas City, Mo. headquarters, but they were
briefed on the agency's findings Thursday, said company spokesman
John Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Til we've had an opportunity to review and fully evaluate the
written citation, it would really be inappropriate for us to offer
further comment,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Site manager Brent Freeman refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Under OSHA rules, the company has 15 days to respond to the
investigation's findings.
</P>
<P>
   The citation was for a serious violation - the second-highest
level of citation OSHA issues. The maximum fine allowed by law for
a serious violation is $7,000.
</P>
<P>
   The company committed another serious violation in August 1999
for an injury to a worker at a power plant construction site in
Agawam, Mass. The company paid a $4,038 fine, OSHA said.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Fitch, whose husband was injured in the Milford accident,
said she is interested in reading the OSHA report.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors had to amputate part of Robert Fitch's right leg to just
above the knee, but they were able to save his left leg. He was
released from the hospital May 25 and still goes for physical
therapy to learn how to use his prothesis and get around.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as his recovery goes, it's very slow and painful,''
Joan Fitch said Friday. ''Mentally, he's still being very
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last month with the New Haven Register, Fitch,
62, said he still hopes to get back on the job someday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I derive the greatest pleasure from operating a crane, just
being in the cab and doing my own thing,'' he said. ''My focus is
to get the pain under control so I can get back to it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
