<HEADLINE> Two people robbed in separate Central Park robberies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Two people - one a tourist from Israel - were
robbed in broad daylight Friday near heavily traveled locations in
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   There were no serious injuries, and police were searching for
the suspects. The robberies did not immediately appear to be
related, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The first robbery occurred at 6:40 a.m. at 62nd Street and East
Drive, near the Central Park Zoo area. James Jonest, 43, of
Manhattan, was approached by two men who punched him in the face
and stomach, taking $253 in cash and his black work jacket that
said ''Rockefeller Center'' on it. Jonest was taken to a nearby
hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not know Jonest's occupation; telephone calls to the
two public relations firms that represent Rockefeller Center were
not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   The second robbery occurred at 11:05 a.m. at 74th Street and
East Drive, near the Central Park Boathouse. Mae Benhur, 23,
visiting from Israel, told police she was approached by a man who
demanded her money. He said he had a gun but did not display one,
Benhur told police.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect took Benhur's CD player, $20 in cash, and a $100
American Express traveler's check, police said.
</P>
