<HEADLINE> Federal government approves $15 million for mudslide repair  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BETHLEHEM, N.Y. (AP) - The Federal Highway Administration has
approved $15 million in emergency funds to help pay the costs
wrought by a May mudslide, Gov. George E. Pataki announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The funds will help restore a main road between this town and
the city of Albany, at least partially closed since the May 16
slide along the Normans Kill Creek. The money also will be used to
relocate the creek's channel to protect the road in the future,
refund costs incurred by emergency services and relocate Albany's
waterline crossing.
</P>
<P>
   A 300-foot chunk of earth slid north into the rain-swelled
Normans Kill. Three days later, a produce market tumbled off the
edge and other businesses and residents have been affected by the
slide.
</P>
<P>
   DOT engineers have been working since to completely reopen the
roadway.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he is still pressing the Clinton administration to
release emergency funding to help businesses hurt by the landslide.
The Federal Emergency Management Agency rejected the initial
request for that funding but Pataki has appealed.
</P>
</TEXT>
