<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NJ--Rabbis Wedding, 610  </HEADLINE>
By BRETT MARTEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (AP) - It's a ''takeover by the rabbis,'' laughed
Rabbi David Goldstein, before, on a more sincere note, commenting
that he was about to take part in a rabbi's dream wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the domed sanctuary of historic Touro Synagogue on
Friday, Goldstein's son, Ari, who is also a rabbi, married Hanna
Yerushalmi, herself both a rabbi and a rabbi's daughter. Both the
bride and groom serve congregations in the Philadelphia area: She
is associate rabbi at Congregation Beth Or in Spring House, Pa.; he
works about 35 miles away, at Congregation M'Kor Shalom in Cherry
Hill, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than a dozen rabbis in the audience, including
the groom's uncle, Joshua Goldstein, who has a congregation in New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi fathers of the bride and groom jointly performed the
ceremony in the reform temple that dates back to 1909.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Zola, a Jewish history professor at Hebrew Union College in
Cincinnati, where the couple also met, said the wedding appeared to
be the first known marriage of two rabbis whose fathers also were
rabbis. Of course, Zola was able to eliminate more than 5,700 years
of Jewish history since women were not permitted to be ordained as
rabbis until about three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   For Hanna, 31, and Ari, 30, the wedding may have made history
but wasn't meant to attract much fanfare. They kept the guest list
down to about 35. Having their fathers preside over the ceremony
simply made the union more memorable, Yerushalmi said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ari and I perform weddings and know the routine and we needed
something to push it over the edge and make it more than routine
for us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The groom is from New Orleans, where his father is the rabbi at
Touro Synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   The uniqueness of the ceremony was evident in several instances,
such as when the couple's parents held the four corners of the
tallit, a ceremonial cloth, above the heads of the bride and groom.
It's a tradition in which officiating rabbis do not usually take
part, never mind two of them at once.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll have one hand up here and one over there,'' directing the
ceremony, said Rabbi Isaac Yerushalmi, who has another daughter
married to a rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Yerushalmi, who grew up in Istanbul, Turkey, and is
now a professor at Hebrew Union, incorporated rituals into the
ceremony associated with Sephardic, Middle Eastern Jews, while the
elder Goldstein presided over portions of the ceremony linked to
Ashkenazi, or European Jewish traditions.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the bride stood on a gold colored carpet while a
wedding song that originated in Greece was sung in Ladin
(pronounced la'DEEN), a folk language of Sephardic Jews, much as
Yiddish is for Ashkenazis.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Yerushalmi also drew up the wedding contract in Aramaic, a
language commonly used by Jews throughout history, even more so
then Hebrew, the rabbi said. Yerushalmi wore traditional Sephardic
garb, including a white robe with lace running down the center from
the collar, and a larger yarmulke which stands more vertically with
a flat top. Goldstein wore the dome-shaped skull cap more commonly
worn by European and American rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   The groom acknowledged he was excited about participating in a
moment of Jewish history but hadn't really considered it until he
and his new bride began discussing wedding plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''At first we were joking about how many rabbis would show up
and then we thought, 'We better be careful about this. It could be
the first time this has ever happened,''' Ari Goldstein said. ''But
it's really about Hanna and how great she is, and when it comes
down to it, I'm just a groom and she's just a bride.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Judaism 101: http://www.jewfaq.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-07-00 1757 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000707.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Harry Potter' Hysteria in England  </HEADLINE>
By AUDREY WOODS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- While truckloads of the top-secret ''Harry Potter
and the Goblet of Fire'' sped along Britain's highways Friday to
shops around the land, bookstores invited youngsters to bring
sleeping bags and await the first official sale -- at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before Harry Potter's new adventure burst upon a waiting
world, it was hard to tell who was more excited -- the book industry
or the throngs of youngsters whose genuine eagerness to read it
created a marketer's dream.
</P>
<P>
   But with the hefty new tome firmly in their grasp, the kids will
have the edge.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're really, REALLY looking forward to it,'' 11-year-old
friends Natasha Cook and Eva Arevuo said almost in unison Friday
afternoon at a Books Etc. branch in north London.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're not so realistic that they're boring,'' Natasha said,
trying to explain the Potter books' appeal. The adventures of the
orphaned wizard, Harry, at Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and
Wizardry are filled with humor, suspense, monsters, ghosts and
magical characters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's always got lots of surprises in it,'' Eva said.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for the new book -- fourth in the series -- to go on
sale, children at Waterstone's bookshop in Piccadilly Circus were
given an ''I waited for Harry'' T-shirt and entertained by a
magician. Waterstone's shops in Glasgow, Scotland, and Birmingham
and Leeds, England, arranged sleepovers, too.
</P>
<P>
   In Aberdeen, Scotland, staff at Ottakars bookshop was renamed
''Pottakars'' for a midnight opening, and staff were dressed up as
witches and wizards.
</P>
<P>
   At the Glasgow Waterstone's, events manager Kim Hardie called
the response to the new book ''absolutely mental'' and said,
''about 80 percent of my time in the last fortnight (two weeks) has
been spent dealing with Harry Potter queries.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Borders shop in Glasgow, Simon Biggam said children will
be offered a Saturday breakfast of Muggle muffins and fizzy
cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've never known anything like it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Amazon.co.uk Internet site promised customers their
pre-ordered copies would go in the mail Friday, with the goal of
getting them delivered by Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Staff at the company's Milton Keynes distribution center in
southern England worked through the night to ensure that about
65,000 copies were ready to ship.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon expects to send 53 tons, or 41.6 million pages worth, of
the book to British readers.
</P>
<P>
   Although it may not have the old-fashioned music of cash
registers ringing in its ears, the U.S. Amazon.com site had totted
up more than 300,000 sales -- more than six times the prepublication
record set in March by John Grisham's latest novel, ''The
Brethren.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire'' occupied the top spot on
the best seller lists of both sites.
</P>
<P>
   The first print run by the book's British and U.S. publishers
totaled 5.3 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Author J.K. Rowling was too busy last year writing this book to
do much publicity for ''Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban,''
the third book in the series.
</P>
<P>
   This time, she's doing book signings on a promotional tour that
sets off on a Hogwarts Express train from ''Platform 9 3/4'' at
King's Cross station, where the boy wizard and his friends embark
each year on their way to adventures.
</P>
<P>
   At 640 pages in Britain and 752 pages in the U.S. edition, the
new book is double the size of ''Harry Potter and the Prisoner of
Azkaban,'' which was greeted with similar excitement when it was
released. It sold 64,000 copies in hardback in its first 2&AMP;frac12; days.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the U.S. bookstore chain Barnes and Noble said it
already had 360,000 pre-orders and expected to break records for
first-day and first-week sales for any book in the company's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Together, its retail stores and Web site already have received
more than 360,000 pre-orders, more than 10 times the number of
pre-orders for any previous book.
</P>
<P>
   Like Waterstone's in Britain, many Barnes and Noble stores are
staying open past midnight to accommodate fans, and planning
special parties with costumes and refreshments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 1801 </TRAILER>
