<DOCNO> APW20000707.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Paroli gets 21 months  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - William Paroli Sr., the former
Dutchess County Republican chairman, was sentenced Friday to 21
months in federal prison for running an extortion scheme, part of
the web of scandal enveloping Poughkeepsie in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   ''You sold out the citizens of Poughkeepsie, whom you were
obliged to serve,'' Judge Barrington Parker told Paroli as the
court imposed a $5,000 fine and $19,300 in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Parker also sentenced Paroli to two years of probation after his
prison term.
</P>
<P>
   Paroli, 72, was ordered to surrender Aug. 21. Parker said he
would recommend a prison near Paroli's home and Paroli thanked him
for his ''understanding and compassion.'' His voice breaking, he
also apologized ''to my family for the embarrassment I caused
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Paroli admitted in February that he conspired to extort payments
from companies doing business in the Town of Poughkeepsie.
According to the 19-count indictment against him, developers and
other businesses were shaken down by town officials working with
Paroli for payoffs that could tally $5,000 or $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has also embroiled the town's former water
superintendent, who was sentenced to 33 months for conspiracy, and
is awaiting trial for allegedly murdering the town's personnel
director.
</P>
<P>
   The town assessor was also found dead as the extortion
investigation began. He apparently committed suicide, officials
have said.
</P>
<P>
   Paroli's attorney, Andrew Rubin, beseeched the judge to sentence
Paroli below federal guidelines, which called for 18 to 24 months.
He said Paroli had already been disgraced and had given up his job
as county elections commissioner. Paroli suffers from prostate
cancer, depression, ulcers, hearing loss, two knee replacements and
a shoulder injury caused by a fall from a tractor, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge said he had already taken it all into
consideration. If not for Paroli's age and cancer, Parker said, ''I
would have dealt with you substantially more harshly.''
</P>
<P>
   Paroli's imprisonment, fine and restitution, Rubin argued, could
endanger his wife's ability to make ends meet. In response, the
judge said Paroli could put off payment of the restitution until
two years after his release.
</P>
<P>
   Paroli would not comment after the sentencing. Prosecutor Cari
Robinson also declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-07-00 1808 </TRAILER>
