<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brooklyn funeral director admits using casino worker to hide winnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - A Brooklyn funeral director admitted Friday
that a casino worker helped him in a bid to avoid reporting
$200,000 he won playing blackjack.
</P>
<P>
   The competition between two casinos for the patronage of Stanley
J. Nieberg played a role in the scheme, records show.
</P>
<P>
   The worker, Louis Freedman, was a marketing host at Trump Taj
Mahal Casino, a job that often involves catering to high-rollers.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators in 1999 revoked the casino licenses of Freedman
and a colleague at the casino, Ronald Citta, in connection with the
Nieberg matter.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Lewis A. Borinsky, who prosecuted
Nieberg, declined to comment on whether charges would be brought
against others.
</P>
<P>
   Nieberg, 47, said that the Taj Mahal and Caesars Atlantic City
Hotel and Casino both courted him by giving him free benefits,
known as ''comps.'' In court, he said he had been the owner of
Memorial Midwood Funeral Chapel for many years.
</P>
<P>
   He was gambling at Caesars in March 1996 and staying in a free
suite when he won the $200,000 and wanted to redeem his
$5,000-chips for cash, Nieberg told U.S. District Judge Stephen M.
Orlofsky.
</P>
<P>
   Casinos, as well as financial institutions, are required to file
currency transaction reports when dealing with more than $10,000 in
cash.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid that, Nieberg said he asked Freedman and others to help
structure the redemption of the chips.
</P>
<P>
   Nieberg said he gave Freedman four of the chips, and Freedman
gave two of the chips to a friend of his, to cash in such a way as
to avoid forcing Caesars to file a report. He did not name
Freedman's friend.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman and Citta lost their credentials because the Casino
Control Commission found they attempted to structure the
redemption, but it ultimately failed, and a report was filed, said
Katherine Lyons, a spokeswoman for the state Division of Gaming
Enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   The commission found that Freedman redeemed the chips in a bid
to retain Nieberg as a Taj Mahal customer, commission spokesman Dan
Heneghan said.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman drove Citta over to Nieberg at Caesars, telling his
colleague, ''We've got a big fish on the hook,'' Heneghan said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission found that Freedman, licensed in May 1979, and
Citta, licensed in May 1981, knew the rules regarding cash
transactions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nieberg lawyer Kenneth F. Hense said his client thought he would
lose his comps because of the big win, and was afraid of being
robbed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the first time he ever won,'' Hense said. ''This was
just an aberrant type thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieberg, reached later, said he knew Freedman from prior
gambling trips. Nieberg said he is now an employee at the funeral
home.
</P>
<P>
   He was released on $100,000 bail pending sentencing Oct. 6,
where he faces up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine on a
single charge of currency structuring. The actual penalties,
however, would be far less, based on federal sentencing guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The judge barred Nieberg from entering any gambling facility or
gambling on the Internet, Borinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. attorney's office in Newark:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-07-00 1830 </TRAILER>
