<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crow from New Rochelle tests positive for West Nile virus  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. (AP) - A crow found dead in New Rochelle last
month has tested positive for the West Nile virus, the first sign
of the disease in Westchester this season, the county Health
Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Other birds with the virus have been found in Rockland County
and in Bergen County, N.J., across the Hudson River from
Westchester, and Friday's finding ''is not totally unexpected,''
said Westchester Health Commissioner Joshua Lipsman.
</P>
<P>
   One of the seven New Yorkers killed by the virus last year was
from Westchester. The county, like most others in the region,
undertook a mosquito-killing campaign over the winter in hopes of
minimizing any outbreak this year.
</P>
<P>
   Health Department inspectors are studying whether the finding
means additional measures against mosquito larvae are needed,
Lipsman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that despite the positive test on the crow - and a
''suspicious'' result on another dead bird - there is no indication
that more pesticide spraying is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer Westchester officials sprayed a pesticide from
helicopters in response to the disease, which was new to the
Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Lipsman noted that infected birds cannot transmit the virus to
people, who get it only from mosquitoes. The virus has yet to be
found in people this year but batches of mosquitoes are being
tested each week.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile virus can cause a range of symptoms. In the most
serious cases, infection can result in encephalitis, or swelling of
the brain, and can be deadly. The elderly and those with
compromised immune systems are most at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
