<HEADLINE> Parents accused of tying up 3-year-old girl  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OLD BRIDGE, N.J. (AP) - The adoptive father of a 3-year-old girl
found tied up alone in an apartment Sunday is in the country
illegally, said police, who also are investigating the immigration
status of the child.
</P>
<P>
   The adoptive mother has an alien resident card, but Old Bridge
police are working with the National Center for Missing and
Exploited Children in Alexandria, Va., to investigate her claims
that Daniela Rojas was adopted three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're working with them to see if in fact it's true or not,''
said Old Bridge police Capt. Robert Bonfante. ''We have a lot of
leg work because (the parents) are not cooperating with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The adoptive father, Romero Simon Rojas, 29, has been charged
with endangering the welfare of a child. Police charged the girl's
adoptive mother, 34-year-old Aracelis Meregildo-Bostic, with child
endangering, criminal restraint and simple assault.
</P>
<P>
   Meregildo-Bostic and Rojas-Romero were released from the
Middlesex County jail Thursday after a bondsman posted $100,000
bail for each.
</P>
<P>
   The case began after a neighbor heard the child crying. An
officer responded to a call and saw Daniela Rojas on the parents'
apartment balcony with her ankles tied together by a nylon sock.
</P>
<P>
   The little girl suffered rope burns and bruises on her wrists
and ankles, police said. Authorities said she was under observation
at St. Peter's University Hospital in New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   She may be released to foster care with her three siblings as
early as this weekend, according to Laurie Facciarossa, a Division
of Youth and Family Services spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The couple are birth parents of three other children, a
3-year-old daughter, a 23-month-old son and a 3-month-old daughter.
DYFS took custody of those children after the parents were arrested
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Police said it looks like the girl was routinely tied up under
her crib by her parents before they went to work in the kitchen of
a nearby restaurant. It was unclear how she made her way onto the
balcony, police said.
</P>
</TEXT>
