<HEADLINE> Assembly poised to consider school construction bill changes  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Two steps remain before New Jersey can
finally commence its long-awaited multibillion dollar school
construction program.
</P>
<P>
   But of those two steps, legislative final passage and the
governor's signature, only the last one is a slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly, which is scheduled to meet Thursday, must agree
with changes made to the plan by Gov. Christie Whitman. Bill
supporters need 41 votes to send it back to her desk.
</P>
<P>
   But Assembly Democrats may not think the governor went far
enough to improve the original Assembly Republican version of the
bill, while Republicans may think she went too far and made it
worse.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is $6 billion for the state's so-called 30 special
needs school districts, and $2.6 billion for all the other schools.
The money is for replacing or renovating old, overcrowded school
buildings. The poor schools would receive full funding under a
state Supreme Court order; all other schools would get state grants
covering at least 40 percent of their costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate last week approved the governor's changes, which are
in the form of a conditional veto of the original Assembly bill.
The lower house last week postponed until July 13 voting to accept
or reject the changes.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Joseph Malone, R-Burlington, the sponsor of the
bill, said he has not spoken to his colleagues in recent days to
determine whether the new bill will attract the needed votes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll see what happens on Thursday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Assembly Democratic Leader Joseph V. Doria,
D-Hudson, said Friday he does not know how many members of his
party will support the bill. Only seven of the 35 Democrats voted
yes on the original version of the bill when it was before the
Assembly last month.
</P>
<P>
   ''Changes were made to the bill to make it more attractive to
some of our members. The question is, are there enough of them to
offset the loss of Republicans who are going to now come off the
bill,'' said Assembly Democratic spokesman Joe Donnelly.
</P>
<P>
   Doria earlier this week wrote a letter to Whitman warning her
not to take Democratic support for granted, as some claimed she did
in 1998 when she unsuccessfully pushed a gas tax hike to fund
highway and mass transit projects.
</P>
<P>
   Malone acknowledged that more of his Republican colleagues may
have concerns about the bill since the governor removed some
provisions popular with party members. For example, she stripped
the bill of legislative oversight of individual school projects in
the special needs districts.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he believes the bill will eventually pass.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it will pass. I think we have to do something,''
Malone said. ''We have to be responsible in fulfilling our
obligation. That does not mean the bill shouldn't be improved.''
</P>
<P>
   David Sciarra of the Education Law Center, which sued the state
on behalf of poor school children, is also confident the bill will
eventually pass.
</P>
<P>
   He said it does not bother him that lawmakers missed the state
Supreme Court's spring deadline to pass the bill to help the poor
schools.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Assembly postpones final passage further, ''then we
have a real serious problem,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-07-00 1905 </TRAILER>
