<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Bar Association talks diversity, Elian at annual meeting  </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The American Bar Association has taken some
steps to diversify the legal profession racially and ethnically,
but much more remains to be done, the organization's outgoing
president said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the group's annual meeting, President William G.
Paul pointed to an ABA scholarship program for minority law
students, which has raised $1.3 million since it was created last
year. Twenty students have been granted scholarships of $15,000,
$5,000 for each year of law school.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 percent of Americans are members of racial or ethnic
minorities, but the nation's lawyers are 92 percent white, Paul has
said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul also spoke of ABA programs that seek to steer minority law
school students to judicial clerkships. Groups such as the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People have complained
that minorities are less likely to be picked for such influential
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can place more people of diverse racial and ethnic
backgrounds, it will accelerate us toward our mission,'' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   The annual meeting of the nation's largest lawyer's group runs
through Tuesday. Paul, of Oklahoma City, is being succeeded by
Martha Barnett, of Tallahassee, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting's panels touch on all aspects of law, including one
Friday that looked at how immigration law will deal with children
in the wake of the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers included Gregory Craig, the attorney for Elian's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez; and Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, who helped
represent the boy's Miami family.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing a question many have raised in the last several months,
the lawyers asked whether the immigration system set up to handle
asylum requests for adults could adequately deal with the needs of
children as young as 6-year-old Elian.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was found floating in an inner tube off the Florida
coast Thanksgiving Day and became the center of a custody battle
between the Miami relatives who cared for him when he landed in the
United States and his father from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives had sought asylum for the boy, but the INS
and U.S. courts rejected the request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-07-00 1912 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000707.0156 </DOCNO>
