<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, July 7, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Puts Off Execution
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton has postponed the first federal
execution since 1963 so the condemned inmate can seek clemency under guidelines
being updated by the government. Convicted killer Juan Raul Garza is one of 21
people, including Oklahoma City bomber Timothy McVeigh, on the federal death
row. ''Given that nearly 40 years have passed since the last prisoner was in
this situation,'' the president ''wants new guidelines that reflect the
realities of today's judicial system and the realities of today's federal
capital cases,'' the White House said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Missile Defense Test Is Tonight
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tonight's $100 million test could move the United States
closer to building a nationwide anti-missile shield. An interceptor rocket from
Kwajalein Atoll in the Pacific will try to shoot down a Minuteman missile with a
dummy warhead from Vandenberg Air Force Base, Calif. It will be the last test
before President Clinton decides whether to pursue construction of a national
missile defense system.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Accused Army Gen. Seeks To Retire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The two-star general accused of sexually harassing the
Army's highest-ranking woman has asked to retire, officials said today. Maj.
Gen. Larry Smith, who denied wrongdoing, was given a written reprimand for
conduct unbecoming an officer and for sexually harassing an officer. He has
submitted his request to retire Sept. 1, His accuser, Lt. Gen. Claudia Kennedy,
said: ''I am satisfied with the Army's action.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
GAO Says Net Agency Has Authority
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional investigators today gave their support to an
organization that sets policies on the domain names used to find Web sites. In a
report to Congress, the General Accounting Office concluded that the U.S.
Commerce Department had the legal authority to let the Internet Corporation for
Assigned Names and Numbers manage the names.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White House Updates Its Web Site
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House launched an updated site on the World Wide
Web today to make it easier for computer users to access government information
from presidential pets to economic indicators. The nearly 6-year-old site --
http://www.whitehouse.gov -- receives 1.2 million hits a week. It was updated to
make it easier for users to navigate with a click of a mouse and offers keyword
searches from any page.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Most U.S. Kids Work by 15
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- At age 12, half of American kids hold informal jobs like
baby-sitting or yard work, and by age 15, nearly two-thirds are employed,
according to a new Labor Department report. ''The American work ethic starts at
an early age,'' said Labor Secretary Alexis Herman of the findings, released by
the Bureau of Labor Statistics today.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New 'Harry Potter' Book Due
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Amazon.com has totaled more than 300,000 sales of ''Harry
Potter and the Goblet of Fire,'' more than six times its previous prepublication
record set in March by John Grisham's novel ''The Brethren.'' The first print
run by the new Harry Potter book's U.S. and British publishers totaled 5.3
million copies. The U.S. bookstore chain Barnes and Noble said it already had
360,000 pre-orders and expected to break its record on Saturday for first-day
sales for any book.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 155; Nasdaq Rises 63
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose strongly today as investors welcomed cooler job
growth, the latest indication that the economy is slowing enough to prevent more
interest rate increases. The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 154.51 at
10,635.98. On the NYSE, gainers led losers by a 9-to-5 margin. The Nasdaq rose
62.63 to 4,023.20.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Auto Racer Kenny Irwin Killed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. (AP) -- Auto racer Kenny Irwin was killed today when his car
slammed into a wall at 150 mph during practice at New Hampshire International
Speedway. Irwin, the rookie of the year in 1998, was entering the third turn
when his car struck the wall and flipped onto its roof during preparations for
the New England 300.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
White Sox 3, Cubs 2, 12 Innings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Frank Thomas hit an RBI single as the Chicago White Sox
pushed across two runs in the 12th inning, and then grabbed Sammy Sosa's liner
and stepped on first to double up Mark Grace in the bottom half to beat the
crosstown Chicago Cubs 4-2 today. White Sox third baseman Herbert Perry, who
saved the game with a great defensive play in the bottom of the 11th, added an
RBI double in the 12th inning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sampras, Rafter in Wimbledon Final
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Pete Sampras sailed into the Wimbledon final today
with a 7-6 (4), 6-2, 6-4 win over qualifier Vladimir Voltchkov, staying on
course for a record 13th Grand Slam title. Sampras will face Patrick Rafter, who
defeated Andre Agassi 7-5, 4-6, 7-5, 4-6, 6-3.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER
</SUBHEAD>
