<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State officials appeal to towns, cities for help with prison expansion </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Struggling to handle a rapidly growing
prison population, state officials are appealing to towns and
cities across the state to consider opening new prisons or expand
existing ones.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal comes as the state faces increasing scrutiny for its
most significant move to ease overcrowding - the transfer of nearly
500 inmates to a maximum-security Virginia prison. Two Connecticut
prisoners have died since being shipped to Wallens Ridge in Big
Stone Gap, Va., the most recent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent Friday to every municipality in Connecticut,
Correction Commissioner John J. Armstrong emphasized the pressing
need for more prison space.
</P>
<P>
   ''The inmate population has grown dramatically in the last few
years and the long-term rate of growth shows no immediate sign of
slowing or reversal,'' Armstrong wrote. ''We ask that you give
serious consideration to submitting a proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has more than 17,000 inmates in 20 prisons, a 22
percent increase from 5 years ago. The inmate population has nearly
doubled in the past decade due to tougher sentencing laws, and is
projected to grow to more than 21,000 prisoners in 2004, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials face an uphill battle in trying to persuade
towns and cities to house a prison.
</P>
<P>
   Cheshire Mayor David Borowy said Friday he would oppose any
expansion to the prison in his town, which houses about 2,500
prisoners. The Cheshire Correctional Institution is near an
elementary school and convalescent home, he said, adding that the
town has had to cope with inmate escapes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're the home to more prisoners than any other town in the
state,'' Borowy said. ''I think we've more than done our share.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fairfield County town of Darien has no prison and is not
interested in opening one, said First Selectman Robert Harrel.
</P>
<P>
   ''The price of land in Darien is not conducive'' to a prison,
Harrel said. ''We're a community that is about 98 percent built
out. It's not something I'd welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Other moves to expand prison space have also met with
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to transfer inmates to Wallens Ridge last October
has sparked allegations of mistreatment and calls for the
prisoners' return in the wake of two deaths this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence James Frazier, 50, lapsed into a coma and died Tuesday
after being shocked repeatedly with a stun gun. In April,
20-year-old David Tracy, of Bridgeport, hung himself in his cell.
</P>
<P>
   While the contract with Virginia has been sharply criticized, a
plan to open a prison at the New Haven armory was squelched in the
Legislature. Local opposition to the project was stiff.
</P>
<P>
   One solution to Connecticut's overcrowded prisons may be to add
extra beds to the state's drug treatment and psychiatric units,
said State Rep. Michael Lawlor, D-East Haven. Lawlor, co-chair of
the Legislature's Judiciary committee, said towns and cities may be
interested in housing new prisons - especially low-security
dormitories for drunken drivers - because of the financial
incentives.
</P>
<P>
   If a town or city agrees to a new prison or an expansion, they
could be eligible for payments in lieu of taxes, jobs for local
residents and increased purchasing of goods and services locally.
</P>
<P>
   State officials also are promising local input in terms of the
size and security level of the prison population to be housed in a
municipality.
</P>
<P>
   An information session is scheduled for 10 a.m. July 26 at the
Maloney Center for Training and Staff Development in Cheshire.
Municipalities have until July 21 to send letters of interest and
until Sept. 1 to complete proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the families of the inmates who died at Wallens Ridge
plan a rally in Bridgeport Saturday to call for an end to the
transfers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-07-00 2016 </TRAILER>
