<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> W.Va. Abortion Law Struck Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- West Virginia's law that restricts
certain late-term abortions is unconstitutional based on a recent
Supreme Court ruling that struck down a similar law in Nebraska, a
federal judge said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Joseph R. Goodwin issued a permanent
injunction that prohibits enforcement of West Virginia's law
banning what opponents call ''partial-birth'' abortion. Goodwin
earlier had stopped the law from going into effect pending the
court's ruling in the Nebraska case, which came June 29.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 West Virginia law said anyone who conducted the
procedure could be found guilty of a felony, imprisoned for two
years and fined up to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin's order cited reasons similar to the Supreme Court's
arguments. The court said the Nebraska law was written too broadly
and could be interpreted to outlaw all abortions, placing an undue
burden on a woman seeking a legal abortion. It also did not include
an exception allowing the procedure to protect a woman's health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
