<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio wraps up five-day campaign swing across New York  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Republican Senate candidate Rick Lazio ended his
week's tour around New York state Friday with visits to a dairy
farm near the Canadian border, a manufacturing plant outside
Rochester and a hospital in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being dogged by reporters' questions for three days
about a fund-raising letter signed by Lazio that claimed Hillary
Rodham Clinton and her husband had ''embarrassed the country and
disgraced their powerful posts'', the Long Island congressman said
he was pleased with the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it was a great success in terms of connecting with
people,'' he said. ''We got a chance to talk about some of the
issues that I've been working on in Washington - housing, in
particular senior housing, veterans issues, issues involving the
agricultural economy here in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trip, which included stops in Yonkers,
Schenectady, Saratoga Springs, Lake Placid, Watertown, Syracuse,
Buffalo and Rochester, Lazio tried to focus on his legislative
record as an eight-term congressman.
</P>
<P>
   His attempts to dictate the debate on issues derailed somewhat
on Wednesday, however, when the four-page fund-raising letter came
to light. He maintained that there was a difference between what a
candidate says in a letter to potential donors and what he says on
the stump.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked again Friday about the scathing wording of the
letter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the letter speaks for itself in terms of some of the
things that have gone on,'' he said at Bronx Lebanon Hospital,
where he was greeted by a small band of protesters shouting:
''You're in the wrong neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time all week that Lazio had been jeered so
lustily.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a great, great week because people have been so
supportive and so kind,'' he said at an appearance with farmers in
Wheatfield, near Niagara Falls. ''They made me feel at home. I feel
like this whole state is my home county now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who was a little-known congressman until New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani dropped out of the Senate and essentially ceded
the Republican nomination to Lazio, also said he was happy with the
level of name recognition he found on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no doubt that we've had, you know, exponential growth
in name ID, name identification, both in the amount of people that
connect with me, support me, know what I stand for,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
