<DOCNO> APW20000707.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Patting down suspects is all part of a
cop's job, so Gov. Christie Whitman said Friday she didn't think
twice before putting her hands on an unarmed Camden man and going
through the motions of a police search.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman acknowledged that a photograph of the search four
years ago likely will inflame allegations that state officials were
insensitive to charges of racial profiling. And the governor said
she fears a public outcry over the photograph will overshadow her
efforts to improve Camden, the state's poorest city.
</P>
<P>
   ''That worries me and for that I am deeply sorry,'' Whitman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't help anybody,'' Whitman said of the photograph,
taken by a law enforcement officer and not previously published.
''It's not something you care to see.''
</P>
<P>
   During an interview with The Associated Press, Whitman
repeatedly defended her search of the unidentified man, saying she
felt a duty to experience exactly the work of police officers who
patrol Camden streets.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to go in and see and experience what I was asking
them to do,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This wasn't a photo opportunity. I wanted to experience
things. I did everything they did that night.''
</P>
<P>
   In a copy of the photograph obtained by AP, Whitman is seen
standing behind what appears to be a black male. His hands are
spread out, palms are pressed against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman is wearing a white sweatshirt, jeans, sneakers and a
baseball cap. Black gloves cover her hands, both of which look to
be pressed against the man's torso.
</P>
<P>
   In the photograph, Whitman appears to be smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman steadfastly rejected any claim that the picture portrays
her or the State Police as biased.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was what it was. It had absolutely nothing to do with
racial profiling,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's absolutely nothing to do with that. He's not a black
suspect. Not a white suspect. It was a suspect. That night there,
it was about crime. It was about drugs,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor now says she would not search suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am definitely not going to do it again,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman joined Camden City police and state troopers for two
nights in early 1996, just after the governor ordered troopers
there to bolster the ranks of local police. Both sessions were not
open to the media, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   During her shifts with the police, Whitman said she went on
several raids, visited crack houses and open air drug markets. Her
time there illustrated the needs for both Camden's residents and
police, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   The man she searched was ''stopped for suspicious activity'' by
the officers and then offered to the governor, Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   He was searched at least once by police officers before he was
presented to the governor so she could search him herself, Whitman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They asked me if I wanted to do this and I said yes,'' Whitman
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They made sure he didn't have any weapons,'' she said. ''It
was really just to see what was involved in that kind of a
search.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she had no idea if she had any legal authority to
conduct a search and she did not ask the officers present if she
was allowed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ''It never occurred to me to ask that question,'' she said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The man never spoke during his brief encounter with the
governor, Whitman said. He never gave Whitman any indication he
knew it was the state's highest elected official who was searching
him.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also said she was unsure if it was legal to hold a
man, search him twice and then let him go.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know that there's anything wrong with that,'' Whitman
said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a problem with the fact that Whitman searched a man
who was apparently never charged by police, said the Rev. Reginald
Jackson, executive director of the Black Ministers Council of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not think there is any reasonable explanation as to why
the chief executive officer of the state would find it acceptable
for a photo opportunity to search a young man,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The photo was turned over to the Attorney General's Office.
Copies of the photograph have been subpoenaed by the lawyer
representing about 30 minority troopers.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the lawsuits by minority troopers, Vincent Bellaran,
Emblez Longoria, Glynn Moore and Marc Stephens said they had been
victims of racial discrimination within the State Police and that
they had seen minority motorists poorly treated by white troopers.
</P>
<P>
   They filed their claim last year after the Attorney General's
Office acknowledged the existence of racial profiling, a practice
in which white troopers pulled over minority drivers based on their
race.
</P>
<P>
   Those same internal investigations said the State Police did not
respond to complaints filed against troopers and that the
department did not hire enough women and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The reports were sparked by the April 1998 shooting by white
troopers of four minority men during a traffic stop on the New
Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   Since the reports were issued, Whitman has appointed a new State
Police superintendent who has begun reforms in hiring and
promotions practices.
</P>
<P>
   Former state police chief Carl Williams adamantly opposed
Whitman's tour of Camden, but was overruled, according to his
lawyer. Williams said it was a ''bad idea for civilians to be
running around pretending to be cops,'' lawyer Clifford Van Syoc
said in May.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman fired Williams in February 1999 after he made public
statements linking minorities to drug suspects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
