<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sex conviction will mean end of priesthood for reverend  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GOSHEN, N.Y. (AP) - The Roman Catholic Church has already begun
proceedings to defrock a priest convicted of sexually abusing boys,
a spokesman for the archdiocese said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Edward A. Pipala has served seven years in a federal
penitentiary after pleading guilty to a federal charge of taking a
minor across state lines to New Jersey for illicit sex. Reports
said he had sex with as many as 50 boys and local charges were
filed as well.
</P>
<P>
   He is due to be released July 23 to an undisclosed location in
Yonkers, the Times Herald-Record of Middletown reported Friday.
Pipala will have to register as a sex offender with local police.
</P>
<P>
   Pipala was pastor at St. John the Evangelist Catholic Church
here and assistant pastor at Sacred Heart Catholic Church in
Monroe.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the two-million member Archdiocese of New York
said late Friday that the church in Rome has begun the process of
laicization, in which a priest is officially returned to lay
status, no longer allowed to perform the duties of a clergyman.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is still a priest (as of Friday) but the process began a
couple of years ago in Rome,'' said Joseph Zwilling, archdiocese
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier published reports indicated the archdiocese didn't know
what would become of Pipala, leading victims and their advocates to
rail against the church.
</P>
<P>
   ''How can there even be a question that he remains a priest?''
said one victim who was not identified. ''He should be in jail
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They've had this guy's paperwork for seven years and they
don't know his status?'' James O'Donnell, a former State Police
major and St. John's parishioner who investigated Pipala, told the
paper. ''He may have repaid his debt to society, but he can never
repay his debt to the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a predator,'' said Orange County District Attorney
Francis D. Phillips, also a parishioner at St. John's. ''I'm not
that optimistic that his lengthy imprisonment has had any effect on
changing his behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Pipala's victims filed more than $500 million in
lawsuits against the priest and the archdiocese. They received
payments estimated at a total of more than a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   During the investigation, Pipala told police the archdiocese
knew of the allegations of pedophilia against him as early as 1977.
Still, he said, they sent him for treatment and then reassigned him
to at least two other parishes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-07-00 2144 </TRAILER>
