<HEADLINE> Colo. Fire Suspect Won't Be Charged  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) -- A man suspected of starting a
campfire that grew to engulf 10,600 acres near Rocky Mountain
National Park will not be charged due to a lack of evidence,
authorities said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The campfire, started June 12, destroyed 22 structures. At the
time, campfires were banned because of dry conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities sought to question Kenneth Winchester, 33, of
Loveland, because his vehicle was seen there the night before the
Bobcat Fire started, Larimer County sheriff's deputy Cindy Gordon
said. No one saw him lighting a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Winchester had declined to talk to authorities. His lawyer, Don
Johnson, did not return a telephone message late Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know the communities touched by this tragic fire will be
disappointed,'' Sheriff Jim Alderden said in a statement. ''But
this is one of those cases where the legal elements establishing
proof beyond a reasonable doubt just weren't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said the department has no other suspects.
</P>
</TEXT>
