<HEADLINE> Maine Hockey Coach Has Surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORONO, Maine (AP) -- Shawn Walsh, who built Maine into a college
hockey power and coached the Black Bears to two national
championships, underwent surgery Friday at a Boston hospital to
remove a cancerous kidney.
</P>
<P>
   His surgeon at the Dana Farber Cancer Institute told WCSH-TV
that the surgery went well.
</P>
<P>
   Urologist Genero Carpinito told the station that Walsh's cancer
had spread to the lymph nodes under his breastbone.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, 45, was told Monday that the kidney was cancerous. He was
cutting back on his speaking engagements, administrative duties and
other tasks away from the team so that he could focus on his
recovery, the university said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The world is full of people who have had to face challenges
like this one,'' Walsh said. ''It's a battle I have to take on and
I am prepared to do so, thankfully with the support of my family
and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials would not discuss the surgery, but the
Portland Press Herald quoted family friends as saying he wanted the
kidney removed as part of an ''aggressive treatment'' designed to
halt the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The Bangor Daily News quoted Walsh as saying he probably will
undergo an intensive 20-day immunal therapy program at UCLA's
Jonsson Cancer Center after he recovers from surgery.
</P>
<P>
   During his 16 years at Maine, Walsh compiled a record of
379-203-37 while winning national championships in 1993 and 1999
and taking the Black Bears on five other trips to the Frozen Four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 2220 </TRAILER>
