<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Randolph Wins NCAA Appeal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- High school basketball star Zach
Randolph won an appeal Friday that will allow him to play at
Michigan State next season despite low scores on an entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
   The university learned that the NCAA granted Randolph
full-qualifier status, spokesman John Lewandowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph, a 6-foot-9, 270-pound center from Marion, Ind., had
the necessary grade-point average required by the NCAA, but he was
20 points shy of the score he needed on the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA did not reveal the reason for its decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm thrilled for Zach Randolph,'' Michigan State coach Tom
Izzo said. ''He made academics a top priority, and all of his hard
work in the classroom has paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Randolph, considered one of the top recruits in the country, was
tempted to jump straight to the NBA out of high school, but his
desire to attend Michigan State was stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph's high school coach, Moe Smedley, said his reluctance
to go pro probably made an impression with the NCAA. Randolph
hadn't been declared eligible by the NCAA when players had to
commit to the NBA draft, but he continued taking the college
entrance exam.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA requires that freshman athletes have at least a 2.0 GPA
in their core classes and a 900 on the SAT. The minimums are on a
sliding scale, which means the higher the GPA, the lower the SAT
can be.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph, who led Marion to a state title, finished high school
with a 2.7 GPA.
</P>
<P>
   He took the SAT at every opportunity in the past year. Randolph
also spent extra hours working with a high school counselor and was
tutored by a Marion student who received a perfect 1,600 on the
test.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 2247 </TRAILER>
