<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressMichael Hartman:
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARION, Ind. (AP) -- Michael Hartman, a guitarist who
collaborated with hard-rock icons David Lee Roth and Steve Vai,
died Thursday following a lifelong battle with cystic fibrosis. He
was 24.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Hartman met famed guitarist Vai through the
Make-A-Wish Foundation. Vai encouraged him to follow his dreams of
being a guitar hero.
</P>
<P>
   After studying at the Musicians Institute in Hollywood, he
joined Roth's band in 1997. Two songs written by Hartman were
included on Roth's album, ''DLR Band,'' released the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, record label Fuel 2000/Universal issued Hartman's solo
instrumental album, ''Black Glue.'' A quote from Vai was listed on
the album's packaging: ''Michael Hartman keeps the spirit of rock
'n' roll alive.''
James Hill:
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- James Hill, the leader and baritone
singer in the legendary gospel group the Fairfield Four, died
Thursday. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1921, the Fairfield Four peaked in popularity after
Hill joined in the mid-1940s.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s the singers recorded three albums and worked with
such stars as John Fogerty, Johnny Cash and Steve Earle.
</P>
<P>
   The group was formed at Nashville's Fairfield Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   The Fairfield Four received the National Heritage Award from The
National Endowment for the Arts in 1989.
Denny Price:
</P>
<P>
   ENID, Okla. (AP) -- Oklahoma Storm co-coach Denny Price, the
father of former NBA star Mark Price and the Vancouver Grizzlies'
Brent Price, died Friday of a heart attack after becoming ill
during a pickup game with his sons at a YMCA. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   Price was athletics director for Phillips University for 12
years. He was an assistant at Oklahoma and with the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the United States Basketball League's Storm earlier
this season as associate coach and became co-coach after Ron Ekker
quit a day before the team was to open play.
James C. Quayle:
</P>
<P>
   SUN CITY WEST, Ariz. (AP) -- James C. Quayle, an Indiana
newspaper publisher and father of former Vice President Dan Quayle,
died Friday. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle was chairman of Huntington Newspapers Inc. in Indiana. He
owned the Huntington Herald-Press with his wife, Corinne Pulliam
Quayle, since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   He was publisher of that newspaper from 1963 to 1990, except for
six years when he was publisher of The Muncie Star and Evening
Press beginning in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's newspaper career began as an advertising salesman in
Lebanon, Ind., in 1945 and The Portsmouth Daily Times in Ohio in
1947. He moved to Huntington in 1948 as advertising manager.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle left Huntington in 1955 to go to Phoenix as public
relations and personnel director for The Arizona Republic and
Phoenix Gazette.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to Huntington in 1963 as publisher and bought the
newspaper the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his wife and son, Quayle is survived by two other sons
and a daughter.
Karl Sweetan:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Karl Sweetan, who went from an 18th-round draft
choice to starting quarterback for the Detroit Lions in one year,
died Sunday of complications from vascular surgery. He was 57.
</P>
<P>
   Sweetan shares the NFL record for the longest touchdown pass
from scrimmage, a 99-yarder to Pat Studstill on Oct. 16, 1966, at
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions chose Sweetan from Wake Forest in 1966. By midseason,
he was Detroit's starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   In 10 games, he completed 157 of 309 passes for 1,809 yards and
four touchdowns, with 14 interceptions. The Lions went 4-9-1 that
season.
Charles Alan Wright:
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Charles Alan Wright, an attorney who
represented President Nixon during the Watergate scandal and argued
against the release of the incriminating Oval Office audiotapes,
died Friday of complications from lung surgery. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's arguments against releasing the Oval Office tapes
earned him national exposure as a constitutional authority and
accolades for his courtroom arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court in 1974 accepted the argument that executive
privilege was a valid concept but ruled 8-0 that Nixon was not
exempt from subpoenas for evidence needed in court cases.
</P>
<P>
   The court ordered Nixon to surrender the tapes, which contained
damaging evidence of White House involvement in covering up the
1972 break-in at the Democratic National Committee offices at the
Watergate. Nixon resigned two weeks later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-07-00 2341 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000707.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-07 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USBL Coach Brent Price Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENID, Okla. (AP) -- Oklahoma Storm co-coach Denny Price, the
father of former NBA star Mark Price and the Vancouver Grizzlies'
Brent Price, died Friday of a heart attack after becoming ill
during a pickup game with his sons at a YMCA.
</P>
<P>
   Price, 62, was athletic director for Phillips University for 12
years, coaching the men's basketball team for seven years and the
women's team for more than two years. He was an assistant at
Oklahoma and with the Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the United States Basketball League's Storm earlier
this season as associate coach and became co-coach after Ron Ekker
quit a day before the team was to open play in April.
</P>
<P>
   Price watched his sons, Brent and Mark, play one series before
deciding to join them. He made a pass to Mark Price for a 3-pointer
and later to Brent Price for a jump shot, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He couldn't get his breath,'' said Ken Rapp, executive
director of the Enid Family YMCA. ''He told me to wait a minute,
and he fell on my shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapp performed CPR until paramedics arrived. Price was
pronounced dead at 1:57 p.m. at Integris Bass Baptist Health Center
in Enid.
</P>
<P>
   Price suffered a heart attack in the late 1980s while coaching
at Phillips but came back to coach later that season after bypass
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Price played college basketball for Georgia Tech and spent
nine of his 12 seasons in the NBA with the Cleveland Cavaliers.
Brent Price played at Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral will be held Monday at Emmanuel Baptist Church in
Enid at 2 p.m., with burial at Memorial Park Cemetery, said the
Rev. Don Tines, the staff minister at Ladusau-Evans Funeral Home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
